WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.200
[Amit Varma]: Before we move on with this episode of the Scene in the Unseen, do check out another

00:00:09.200 --> 00:00:18.640
[Amit Varma]: awesome podcast from IVM Podcast, Cyrus Says, hosted by my old buddy, Cyrus Brocha.

00:00:18.640 --> 00:00:23.560
[Amit Varma]: The 2019 general elections are upon us and it's a good time to ask, what do our political

00:00:23.560 --> 00:00:29.120
[Amit Varma]: parties believe in? Most parties espouse principles only as a matter of positioning in the political

00:00:29.120 --> 00:00:33.840
[Amit Varma]: marketplace. They will say anything and do anything that gets them votes. They are immoral

00:00:33.840 --> 00:00:38.280
[Amit Varma]: and sociopathic. You vote for them on the basis of what you want in that political marketplace

00:00:38.280 --> 00:00:42.600
[Amit Varma]: and how credibly they can deliver that. But there is one political party in India that

00:00:42.600 --> 00:00:47.520
[Amit Varma]: is clearly different. The BJP does seem to have certain core beliefs. And because they

00:00:47.520 --> 00:00:52.720
[Amit Varma]: are the biggest political player around, and because beliefs have consequences, it is worth

00:00:52.720 --> 00:00:58.440
[Amit Varma]: examining their philosophy. What is this Hindutva thing? What is this Hindu Rashtra that so

00:00:58.440 --> 00:01:03.960
[Amit Varma]: many people aspire to? What does it mean for our nation that the BJP's idea of India is

00:01:03.960 --> 00:01:10.360
[Amit Varma]: so exclusionary, so full of resentments from the past, so dependent on identity? And most

00:01:10.360 --> 00:01:28.840
[Amit Varma]: importantly, what are its intellectual foundations? Welcome to the scene and the unseen, our weekly

00:01:28.840 --> 00:01:29.840
[Amit Varma]: podcast on economics, politics and behavioral science. Please welcome your host, Amit Badma.

00:01:29.840 --> 00:01:32.360
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to the scene and the unseen. My guest today is Aakar Patel, a journalist and columnist

00:01:32.360 --> 00:01:38.080
[Amit Varma]: whose work I have been reading since the 1990s, who is often provocative, usually insightful,

00:01:38.080 --> 00:01:42.560
[Amit Varma]: and always worth reading. I asked Aakar to come on the show as a guest in the expectation

00:01:42.560 --> 00:01:47.320
[Amit Varma]: of nothing other than a stimulating conversation, and I didn't have a subject in mind for him.

00:01:47.320 --> 00:01:51.840
[Amit Varma]: Then Aakar mentioned that he's writing a book called Our Hindu Rashtra, which will be released

00:01:51.840 --> 00:01:56.280
[Amit Varma]: by Westland later this year. It made perfect sense to talk about that, especially with

00:01:56.280 --> 00:02:02.200
[Amit Varma]: these ongoing elections, to take a closer look at what is fast becoming an idea of India

00:02:02.200 --> 00:02:07.680
[Amit Varma]: that has gained immense traction in the last few years. What is Hindutva exactly? Why has

00:02:07.680 --> 00:02:13.040
[Amit Varma]: it become so popular recently? What are its intellectual foundations? I got the stimulating

00:02:13.040 --> 00:02:19.400
