00:03:19.200 --> 00:03:26.320
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to the scene in the unseen. Thank you. Before we get going talking about the

00:03:26.320 --> 00:03:29.840
[Amit Varma]: book that you're writing and the subject at hand, tell me a little bit about yourself.

00:03:29.840 --> 00:03:34.880
[Amit Varma]: You've been a journalist, right since the early 90s. And now you had amnesty in India.

00:03:34.880 --> 00:03:41.200
[Guest]: What's your journey been like? Sure. I'm from Surat. And I moved to Bombay in 94 at the

00:03:41.200 --> 00:03:49.760
[Guest]: end of 94. Looking for work and the sort of easiest work one could find with not much

00:03:49.760 --> 00:03:55.840
[Guest]: qualification was in journalism then. I think the case is the same now. And I worked in

00:03:55.840 --> 00:04:03.920
[Guest]: newspapers till 2005. I ran a business for a few years after that. And then I retired.

00:04:03.920 --> 00:04:09.960
[Guest]: And five years after that, I got a job in a nonprofit, which is where I am now.

00:04:09.960 --> 00:04:13.440
[Amit Varma]: And you've kind of been a prolific columnist, even now. And you know, as someone who is

00:04:13.440 --> 00:04:17.560
[Amit Varma]: also a columnist, one of the things I marvel at is how much prolific you are, how many

00:04:17.560 --> 00:04:22.600
[Guest]: columns you actually get. So there is a tradition in the language papers

00:04:22.600 --> 00:04:28.920
[Guest]: of South Asia, whether they are in Gujarati, Hindi, Marathi, Urdu, where you have somebody

00:04:28.920 --> 00:04:36.440
[Guest]: who is like an autodidact, not a specialist, and a regular writer. So any newspaper in

00:04:36.440 --> 00:04:43.480
[Guest]: Pakistan or in Bangladesh or in Surat will have such people who work for newspapers,

00:04:43.480 --> 00:04:49.640
[Guest]: who write three, four times a week. So I think I come from that tradition. So writing is

00:04:49.640 --> 00:04:53.960
[Guest]: easy, and it gets easier when you do it more and more.

00:04:53.960 --> 00:04:57.480
[Amit Varma]: And you had a deep interest in Urdu also, I believe you started learning it in the 1990s.

00:04:57.480 --> 00:05:02.120
[Amit Varma]: You've written a lot about it. Tell me about that interest and how it's kind of...

00:05:02.120 --> 00:05:09.880
[Guest]: I worked in a newspaper that also had a Murdu edition, which sort of fascinated me. And

00:05:09.880 --> 00:05:15.320
[Guest]: I thought I should try and learn the script. And then the series of Malwis came home, this

00:05:15.320 --> 00:05:20.680
[Guest]: was in early 2000. And they taught me how to read it. And at some point, I figured out

00:05:20.680 --> 00:05:25.720
[Guest]: that this was just the Hindi that I knew from Bollywood, written a different way. So the

00:05:25.720 --> 00:05:31.240
[Guest]: mystery and the romance left at that point. But I knew the language sufficiently to be

00:05:31.240 --> 00:05:36.120
[Guest]: able to do some basic translations. And I did that.

00:05:36.120 --> 00:05:41.840
[Guest]: And you also translated Montauk's works. Yes. So he's quite an interesting writer.

00:05:41.840 --> 00:05:47.680
[Guest]: He was autodidactic himself, didn't pass out of college, and wrote very simply, I think

00:05:47.680 --> 00:05:51.760
[Guest]: he wrote the kind of language that you and I would recognize as being Hindi. He would

00:05:51.760 --> 00:05:58.040
[Guest]: call it Urdu. So it wasn't that difficult. The perso-Arabic content, which tends to define

00:05:58.040 --> 00:06:00.760
[Guest]: Urdu in our time was fairly low in his writing.

00:06:00.760 --> 00:06:04.600
[Amit Varma]: In fact, just this issue itself about how there was this common sort of bhaasha called

00:06:04.600 --> 00:06:09.800
[Amit Varma]: Hindustani and then out of that you had this movement to separate Urdu and Hindi and then,

00:06:09.800 --> 00:06:13.880
[Amit Varma]: you know, also speaks to a bit about what we're talking about today, doesn't it? Is

00:06:13.880 --> 00:06:17.720
[Guest]: that part of the nationalism? Indeed, indeed. I think you're dead right.

00:06:17.720 --> 00:06:24.240
[Guest]: I think with both with the movement that happened in the heartland, Bhartendu, Harishchandra

00:06:24.240 --> 00:06:31.400
[Guest]: and so on in the 19th century, and whatever happened with Urdu after 1947 in Pakistan

00:06:31.400 --> 00:06:37.920
[Guest]: and here is part of that narrative that you try to hold on to your nationalism through

00:06:37.920 --> 00:06:43.200
[Guest]: the script, and the language then changes. Pakistanis that I know think that Bollywood

00:06:43.200 --> 00:06:49.160
[Guest]: is, is actually their language, Urdu. And when I asked them what they think Hindi is,

00:06:49.160 --> 00:06:53.040
[Guest]: they would say something like, it's what Vajpayee speaks, you know, whereas we would listen

00:06:53.040 --> 00:06:57.960
[Guest]: to Jio TV or one of the Pakistani stations, and it would not be that easy for us to pick

00:06:57.960 --> 00:07:04.680
[Guest]: it out. I think the vocabulary has changed a bit across the border. The grammar of course

00:07:04.680 --> 00:07:05.720
[Amit Varma]: remains the same.

00:07:05.720 --> 00:07:10.320
[Amit Varma]: And one of the things that I can't often figure out is that when Modi gives many of his speeches

00:07:10.320 --> 00:07:14.360
[Amit Varma]: like his addresses to the nation and chooses to speak in Hindi, he's not actually speaking

00:07:14.360 --> 00:07:18.320
[Amit Varma]: in the regular colloquial Hindi in which you and I might converse, but a shuddh form of

00:07:18.320 --> 00:07:23.000
[Amit Varma]: it using those shuddh Hindi terms. And I've always wondered that if if he is trying to

00:07:23.000 --> 00:07:28.000
[Amit Varma]: spread his thing as a national leader, isn't that strategically unwise? Or does that in

00:07:28.000 --> 00:07:30.200
[Amit Varma]: itself imply some kind of message and positioning?

00:07:30.200 --> 00:07:35.380
[Guest]: That's a good question. I think there are many Hindis and I think the one that he uses,

00:07:35.380 --> 00:07:43.840
[Guest]: I would say is less stripped of what we would call Hindustani than a lot of other people.

00:07:43.840 --> 00:07:51.240
[Guest]: I think Vajpayee wrote a much more Sanskritized form of the language. Mr. Modi comes out of

00:07:51.240 --> 00:07:58.400
[Guest]: a tradition where in Gujarati, it's been a language which has had access to Arabic and

00:07:58.400 --> 00:08:05.720
[Guest]: Farsi for a very long time. And the modern Gujarati vocabulary is not dependent on, for

00:08:05.720 --> 00:08:12.840
[Guest]: instance, English, to be able to have sophisticated communication in commerce. So we have words

00:08:12.840 --> 00:08:18.720
[Guest]: like say Hundi or Hawala, which are bad words, otherwise outside of Gujarat. But for a Gujarati,

00:08:18.720 --> 00:08:24.360
[Guest]: they would purely be these are both words from our area would just be purely words that

00:08:24.360 --> 00:08:30.040
[Guest]: would represent transactions. So I think he would be using a lot of Farsi words, you know,

00:08:30.040 --> 00:08:37.240
[Guest]: we call a door a Darwajo, which is actually a Persian word. And, and so on. So I don't

00:08:37.240 --> 00:08:45.720
[Guest]: think that it's as stripped as Mr. Vajpayee's was. But it is, as you say, fairly Sanskritized

00:08:45.720 --> 00:08:46.720
[Amit Varma]: in many ways.

00:08:46.720 --> 00:08:50.320
[Amit Varma]: Like just the use of the word Mitro and I could be wrong here, but it seems to me that

00:08:50.320 --> 00:08:54.600
[Amit Varma]: Mitro is not something people would use in normal conversation, let's say Dosto or Yaro

00:08:54.600 --> 00:09:00.940
[Guest]: or whatever. And, yeah, he has a bit of a style to him. So I think he he's quite studied

00:09:00.940 --> 00:09:09.280
[Guest]: in the way that he approaches his public image quite seriously. And he would have given a

00:09:09.280 --> 00:09:15.840
[Guest]: great deal of thought to how to present himself and what what should the catchphrases be is

00:09:15.840 --> 00:09:21.440
[Guest]: the kind of guy who spends a lot of time thinking about this. So before we kind of get to your

00:09:21.440 --> 00:09:27.440
[Amit Varma]: book, you know, we are recording this on March 28, the episode comes out on April 8. What

00:09:27.440 --> 00:09:32.080
[Amit Varma]: do you think is, you know, is going to happen in these elections? What's your?

00:09:32.080 --> 00:09:37.500
[Guest]: My sense is that we'll have a hung parliament. And I my sense is that it will be more hung

00:09:37.500 --> 00:09:45.080
[Guest]: than people think it's going to be. And I think that's a good thing. I think that the

00:09:45.080 --> 00:09:50.520
[Guest]: more parties that have access to the pie in Delhi, the more levers you have for civil

00:09:50.520 --> 00:09:57.080
[Guest]: society, us, you know, NGO, we don't have that much to hold on to when there is a single

00:09:57.080 --> 00:10:02.160
[Guest]: party that rules Delhi, there's absolutely nobody that listens to you, particularly on

00:10:02.160 --> 00:10:07.560
[Guest]: the difficult subjects. And I think that the more divided the share of power is, the better

00:10:07.560 --> 00:10:12.860
[Guest]: it is for this country, the more voices are heard, the more the deeper the representation.

00:10:12.860 --> 00:10:24.080
[Guest]: So my hope, at least if not my, my, my studied sort of, you know, analysis is that there

00:10:24.080 --> 00:10:27.480
[Guest]: will be a hung parliament and it will be more hung than people think it will be.

00:10:27.480 --> 00:10:30.880
[Amit Varma]: No, it's a great thing for another reason, in the sense that you automatically then have

00:10:30.880 --> 00:10:36.320
[Amit Varma]: more checks and balances and at a time when institutions are being eroded anyway, that,

00:10:36.320 --> 00:10:37.320
[Amit Varma]: you know, might be useful.

00:10:37.320 --> 00:10:40.600
[Guest]: Well, the counter to what you're saying, and I completely agree with you, or the counter

00:10:40.600 --> 00:10:45.280
[Guest]: to what you're saying might well be the fact that, okay, look at say, UP at two, when you

00:10:45.280 --> 00:10:52.040
[Guest]: have a weak center, and when you don't have a central figure of authority, then the periphery

00:10:52.040 --> 00:10:56.920
[Guest]: and the ministries do you know, whatever they want to and so it's sort of, you know, double

00:10:56.920 --> 00:11:04.120
[Guest]: edged, but I on the whole think that South Asia generally is better off when power at

00:11:04.120 --> 00:11:08.880
[Guest]: the center is split, and it's not unified in the form of either a person definitely

00:11:08.880 --> 00:11:12.000
[Guest]: not in the form of a person or a party.

00:11:12.000 --> 00:11:13.960
[Amit Varma]: So let's let's talk about your book now.

00:11:13.960 --> 00:11:16.080
[Amit Varma]: Your book is about the Hindu Rashtra, right?

00:11:16.080 --> 00:11:18.600
[Amit Varma]: And you've been writing about this for donkey's years.

00:11:18.600 --> 00:11:21.200
[Amit Varma]: What made you interested in the subject?

00:11:21.200 --> 00:11:23.720
[Amit Varma]: I mean, over time, how have your thoughts on this evolved?

00:11:23.720 --> 00:11:30.360
[Guest]: Well, coming from Surat, I had this sort of traditional middle class upbringing, very

00:11:30.360 --> 00:11:37.720
[Guest]: Hindu, where the access to diversity was fairly low.

00:11:37.720 --> 00:11:43.200
[Guest]: You did have, say, Muslims in your class, but because it was a school that was middle

00:11:43.200 --> 00:11:50.160
[Guest]: class, and English, there wasn't as much representation of the society that you would be in.

00:11:50.160 --> 00:11:55.560
[Guest]: And once you left school, Surat is fairly ghettoized, so it's it's a very old city.

00:11:55.560 --> 00:12:01.040
[Guest]: The Brits came there in 1608, but it was already a big city, then Tolstoy wrote a short story

00:12:01.040 --> 00:12:05.640
[Guest]: called the coffee house of Surat, where he says that a lot of people from around the

00:12:05.640 --> 00:12:10.000
[Guest]: world, you know, Chinese people and Armenians and all gather and talk about life.

00:12:10.000 --> 00:12:14.320
[Guest]: And it's true that it was a port city till the 18th century, it was both globalized and

00:12:14.320 --> 00:12:15.320
[Guest]: ghettoized.

00:12:15.320 --> 00:12:17.040
[Guest]: It was both globalized and ghettoized.

00:12:17.040 --> 00:12:18.360
[Guest]: Very, very true.

00:12:18.360 --> 00:12:22.600
[Guest]: It had access because of its port, it has a very sheltered port, or it did actually

00:12:22.600 --> 00:12:24.800
[Guest]: now it's silted over.

00:12:24.800 --> 00:12:26.780
[Guest]: But the port is inland from the sea.

00:12:26.780 --> 00:12:32.240
[Guest]: So you could have fairly large ships come into the Arabian Sea and then come into Surat

00:12:32.240 --> 00:12:38.520
[Guest]: and but then be on a river, the Tapi, which which cuts India in half, east to west.

00:12:38.520 --> 00:12:44.560
[Guest]: And so it had access to the Portuguese and the Dutch and the English and so on, much

00:12:44.560 --> 00:12:46.440
[Guest]: before the rest of India did.

00:12:46.440 --> 00:12:48.800
[Guest]: It was the primary port of the Mughal Empire.

00:12:48.800 --> 00:12:51.600
[Guest]: So it was where Hajj left from.

00:12:51.600 --> 00:12:59.240
[Guest]: And it was this city and is this city which was segregated in terms of caste.

00:12:59.240 --> 00:13:04.880
[Guest]: So you had something called a Sheri, which is a lane with a single mouth.

00:13:04.880 --> 00:13:08.640
[Guest]: And you've got homes on both sides, you know, sharing walls of one caste.

00:13:08.640 --> 00:13:15.720
[Guest]: So my mom grew up in a place called Sidh Matani Sheri, which is the neighborhood of the of

00:13:15.720 --> 00:13:19.840
[Guest]: this goddess called Sidh Mata and it was full of partidar homes.

00:13:19.840 --> 00:13:24.960
[Guest]: So when I go back to Surat, a lot of the neighbors there are still from the same caste and it's

00:13:24.960 --> 00:13:26.680
[Guest]: sort of remained that way.

00:13:26.680 --> 00:13:30.920
[Guest]: And how did that shape the young man you were?

00:13:30.920 --> 00:13:37.280
[Guest]: One big difference between me and a lot of the other people from my background was the

00:13:37.280 --> 00:13:43.000
[Guest]: fact that I went to a school there, where I was taught English.

00:13:43.000 --> 00:13:47.720
[Guest]: So Surat at that point had four schools, it was a city of about 25 or 30 lakh people,

00:13:47.720 --> 00:13:55.840
[Guest]: but there were only four schools that taught English, three of them set up by the missionaries

00:13:55.840 --> 00:14:00.240
[Guest]: and one by the Parsis, Hindus who were 90% of the school's population had not built a

00:14:00.240 --> 00:14:02.080
[Guest]: single one.

00:14:02.080 --> 00:14:06.720
[Guest]: But that access to the language gave one access then to books.

00:14:06.720 --> 00:14:10.680
[Guest]: There was there was one bookstore in Surat then, like a very large city.

00:14:10.680 --> 00:14:15.680
[Guest]: But whatever I could get my hands on, I would read and that sort of opened up the world

00:14:15.680 --> 00:14:21.360
[Guest]: in a way that would not have had I been like the rest of my cousins and so on, not in an

00:14:21.360 --> 00:14:22.840
[Amit Varma]: English school.

00:14:22.840 --> 00:14:27.200
[Amit Varma]: And how was it that you know, was there a time when you began to feel that you were

00:14:27.200 --> 00:14:29.220
[Amit Varma]: apart from them in the way you looked at the world?

00:14:29.220 --> 00:14:32.760
[Amit Varma]: Because I'm assuming that in that kind of background, if you grow up, you are pretty

00:14:32.760 --> 00:14:36.920
[Amit Varma]: much someone who is going to grow up a Modi supporter, for example.

00:14:36.920 --> 00:14:41.400
[Guest]: Yeah, so the BJP has become the party of Hindus in that state.

00:14:41.400 --> 00:14:46.480
[Guest]: That's why we see very remarkable things like a vote share of more than 50%, which is very

00:14:46.480 --> 00:14:50.880
[Guest]: unusual in democratic politics anywhere, but particularly in this country, because what

00:14:50.880 --> 00:14:56.080
[Guest]: happens usually in our country is that you've got two dominant castes.

00:14:56.080 --> 00:15:01.200
[Guest]: Let's say in Karnataka, we are in Bangalore now, you've got the Karega and you've got

00:15:01.200 --> 00:15:02.200
[Guest]: the Lingayat.

00:15:02.200 --> 00:15:11.280
[Guest]: So they would they would they would be a kind of a primary war over who would get access

00:15:11.280 --> 00:15:13.680
[Guest]: to the state and the goodies that the state gives.

00:15:13.680 --> 00:15:15.560
[Guest]: So it's usually that way.

00:15:15.560 --> 00:15:19.520
[Guest]: What's happened in Gujarat is that though it started out that way, where the division

00:15:19.520 --> 00:15:25.360
[Guest]: was basically the party that community supporting the BJP, which it does still the majority

00:15:25.360 --> 00:15:31.720
[Guest]: of all BJP cabinets that have been formed in that state since 95 have comprised of the

00:15:31.720 --> 00:15:33.640
[Guest]: Patel community.

00:15:33.640 --> 00:15:39.480
[Guest]: And the other community was the New York Shatria or what is called Thakur Darbar these these

00:15:39.480 --> 00:15:43.080
[Guest]: words which went to the Congress.

00:15:43.080 --> 00:15:51.440
[Guest]: But what has happened is that the split is not even seats that are reserved, for instance,

00:15:51.440 --> 00:15:57.720
[Guest]: for the schedule castes and the schedule tribes tend to go to the BJP entirely.

00:15:57.720 --> 00:16:00.720
[Guest]: And the Congress has stayed there in almost permanent opposition.

00:16:00.720 --> 00:16:07.840
[Guest]: I'm 49 years old, I came into the age of voting in 1988.

00:16:07.840 --> 00:16:13.720
[Guest]: Every single Lok Sabha election that I have been old enough to vote for there has been

00:16:13.720 --> 00:16:15.600
[Guest]: won by one BJP man.

00:16:15.600 --> 00:16:19.560
[Guest]: Of course, he was denied a ticket after Mr. Modi came to power.

00:16:19.560 --> 00:16:23.040
[Guest]: But Kashi Ramlana was the guy who represented Surat.

00:16:23.040 --> 00:16:28.240
[Guest]: And from being somebody who was 18 or 19 to somebody who was in his 40s to have the same

00:16:28.240 --> 00:16:33.560
[Guest]: person represent them, it's very unusual for the city especially.

00:16:33.560 --> 00:16:37.800
[Guest]: But that's how Gujarat has has come to be.

00:16:37.800 --> 00:16:41.400
[Amit Varma]: And as a young journalist, I mean, if you sort of look at the arc of your career at

00:16:41.400 --> 00:16:46.040
[Amit Varma]: the start of your career, the Hindutva or the Hindu Rashtra or whatever was just about

00:16:46.040 --> 00:16:48.600
[Amit Varma]: exploding with Babri and all of that.

00:16:48.600 --> 00:16:53.960
[Amit Varma]: And now it's kind of taken over the country in a sense.

00:16:53.960 --> 00:16:55.960
[Amit Varma]: What was your approach to it then?

00:16:55.960 --> 00:16:57.640
[Guest]: And you know, did you see this coming?

00:16:57.640 --> 00:16:59.040
[Guest]: No, I didn't.

00:16:59.040 --> 00:17:07.560
[Guest]: And it was like an episode then it seemed like something which was extraordinary, which

00:17:07.560 --> 00:17:14.760
[Guest]: was behind us and I wasn't old enough or sort of mature enough certainly to be able to understand

00:17:14.760 --> 00:17:17.280
[Guest]: what it had done, what that moment meant.

00:17:17.280 --> 00:17:20.840
[Guest]: I had celebrated the night when the mosque was torn down.

00:17:20.840 --> 00:17:25.160
[Guest]: I was with some friends and it seemed like a very big moment that something something

00:17:25.160 --> 00:17:26.160
[Guest]: big had happened.

00:17:26.160 --> 00:17:27.160
[Guest]: You celebrated?

00:17:27.160 --> 00:17:28.160
[Guest]: I was excited.

00:17:28.160 --> 00:17:29.840
[Guest]: I mean, I don't know if the word is celebrate.

00:17:29.840 --> 00:17:33.800
[Guest]: But I was sort of I wouldn't say that I was disappointed.

00:17:33.800 --> 00:17:36.800
[Guest]: I wasn't sad or like anything else.

00:17:36.800 --> 00:17:42.080
[Guest]: That's the background that one grew up in, you know, the Muslims were them and we were

00:17:42.080 --> 00:17:48.360
[Guest]: the we and then we had done something big and then.

00:17:48.360 --> 00:17:57.040
[Guest]: But no, in the mid 90s, it had not occurred to me that this is that event was not just

00:17:57.040 --> 00:18:00.520
[Guest]: one moment, but it was something that would live with us for a long time.

00:18:00.520 --> 00:18:04.880
[Amit Varma]: So sort of two related questions, I guess, when did you start to realize that it was

00:18:04.880 --> 00:18:10.840
[Amit Varma]: a process and it was becoming something and when did you also start to change from a position

00:18:10.840 --> 00:18:13.200
[Amit Varma]: of looking at the world through that we or them thing?

00:18:13.200 --> 00:18:19.480
[Guest]: I think moving to Bombay, it was still called Bombay when I moved.

00:18:19.480 --> 00:18:24.760
[Guest]: Did some of that, that you had access to people who are much smarter than you.

00:18:24.760 --> 00:18:30.440
[Guest]: And in the newsroom in those days, that was that was fairly sort of easy to come by very

00:18:30.440 --> 00:18:34.560
[Guest]: bright people came to work for very little money.

00:18:34.560 --> 00:18:38.120
[Guest]: People who are much better at than you and you worked with women.

00:18:38.120 --> 00:18:43.120
[Guest]: I had never worked with a woman before in my life.

00:18:43.120 --> 00:18:48.680
[Guest]: And this sort of sort of opens up your eyes if you are in any way open minded in a way

00:18:48.680 --> 00:18:53.760
[Guest]: that very few things will because in a very brief period of time, you are exposed to people

00:18:53.760 --> 00:18:59.040
[Guest]: who are smarter than you come from a different background, who might be from a gender that

00:18:59.040 --> 00:19:02.640
[Guest]: you didn't think as being, you know, belonging in the workplace.

00:19:02.640 --> 00:19:06.800
[Guest]: So you have you have an education drilled into you fairly, fairly quickly.

00:19:06.800 --> 00:19:11.560
[Guest]: So I think by the mid 90s, yeah, I was there.

00:19:11.560 --> 00:19:16.280
[Guest]: I also encountered some people whose writing stayed with me for a very long time.

00:19:16.280 --> 00:19:24.200
[Guest]: And there's a man called Khalid Ahmed, who writes for the Express here in India.

00:19:24.200 --> 00:19:35.920
[Guest]: He's he's a Lahori, he's a former diplomat in the Pakistani Foreign Service, a former

00:19:35.920 --> 00:19:43.280
[Guest]: newspaper editor, both in Urdu, in English, he wrote for a paper called the Frontier Post

00:19:43.280 --> 00:19:44.480
[Guest]: in Zia's period.

00:19:44.480 --> 00:19:50.080
[Guest]: So that was not an easy time for journalists, definitely not for somebody who was a proper

00:19:50.080 --> 00:19:52.640
[Guest]: intellectual, which which he is.

00:19:52.640 --> 00:19:53.880
[Guest]: And he was bilingual.

00:19:53.880 --> 00:19:57.100
[Guest]: So I think that really attracted me to him.

00:19:57.100 --> 00:20:02.560
[Guest]: What we have on the subcontinent generally, and in this country in particular, is that

00:20:02.560 --> 00:20:11.760
[Guest]: the intellectual narrative belongs to a group of people who are more or less a monolingual

00:20:11.760 --> 00:20:17.640
[Guest]: that they can read in their own language, but they do not regularly read in it.

00:20:17.640 --> 00:20:19.440
[Guest]: And they certainly don't write it.

00:20:19.440 --> 00:20:20.720
[Guest]: He was different in that sense.

00:20:20.720 --> 00:20:25.760
[Guest]: So he brought he brought up a perspective, which was quite unique, and I would recommend

00:20:25.760 --> 00:20:29.400
[Guest]: to those people who are sort of listening to this to try and find some of his stuff.

00:20:29.400 --> 00:20:30.400
[Amit Varma]: Khalid Ahmed.

00:20:30.400 --> 00:20:33.980
[Amit Varma]: So how did you again come to the subject of the book, the Hindu Rashtra?

00:20:33.980 --> 00:20:35.240
[Guest]: So I think we are living with it.

00:20:35.240 --> 00:20:43.080
[Guest]: I think what happened in Gujarat in 2002, when I was there, then I'd gone back to that

00:20:43.080 --> 00:20:47.520
[Guest]: state with with a group of people that were doing a study.

00:20:47.520 --> 00:20:52.160
[Guest]: And at that point, it sort of occurred to me that this this was not something that we

00:20:52.160 --> 00:20:57.480
[Guest]: should treat as being episodic, that we had a riot in 69, and then we had a riot in 84,

00:20:57.480 --> 00:21:00.380
[Guest]: and then we had a riot in 93, and then so on.

00:21:00.380 --> 00:21:02.240
[Guest]: This was something different.

00:21:02.240 --> 00:21:06.160
[Guest]: And this this was going to stay with us for a very long time.

00:21:06.160 --> 00:21:08.800
[Guest]: And it began then, I think.

00:21:08.800 --> 00:21:18.240
[Guest]: And then I started reading some of the stuff that was that underpins the BJP and the RSS.

00:21:18.240 --> 00:21:21.960
[Guest]: I read the stuff that the Prime Minister wrote.

00:21:21.960 --> 00:21:27.400
[Guest]: And so it didn't occur to me that that there was a book in it.

00:21:27.400 --> 00:21:33.360
[Guest]: But I think the last four and a half years, I think, solidified the idea that there is

00:21:33.360 --> 00:21:38.920
[Guest]: something that is compact that can be written and explained to people.

00:21:38.920 --> 00:21:42.200
[Amit Varma]: And one of the things that sort of struck me when, you know, when we fixed up the time

00:21:42.200 --> 00:21:45.120
[Amit Varma]: for this episode, and I thought I should prep for it.

00:21:45.120 --> 00:21:50.620
[Amit Varma]: And I tried to look for books on the subject of Hindutva and the intellectual traditions

00:21:50.620 --> 00:21:53.720
[Amit Varma]: behind it and discovered a paucity of such material.

00:21:53.720 --> 00:21:57.800
[Guest]: There's just practically no, yeah, there's not much there, unfortunately.

00:21:57.800 --> 00:22:04.360
[Guest]: So if you look at the subcontinent, if you look at religious conservatism, almost all

00:22:04.360 --> 00:22:11.760
[Guest]: of it at the properly intellectual level is Muslim.

00:22:11.760 --> 00:22:24.000
[Guest]: So if we think of radical Islamist groups, Al-Qaeda and the Muslim Brotherhood, their

00:22:24.000 --> 00:22:28.080
[Guest]: thinking is underpinned by a man who came out of Maharashtra.

00:22:28.080 --> 00:22:34.800
[Guest]: It wasn't called that then, a Morangabad, a man called Madhudi, self-taught, but smart

00:22:34.800 --> 00:22:40.880
[Guest]: enough to look at the modern world and build a structure that responded to the modern world

00:22:40.880 --> 00:22:44.000
[Guest]: from the perspective of his faith.

00:22:44.000 --> 00:22:50.020
[Guest]: We didn't have that happen from the Hindu thinkers.

00:22:50.020 --> 00:22:59.520
[Guest]: So that's true, that radicalism and response to modernity from the perspective of a faith

00:22:59.520 --> 00:23:06.000
[Guest]: that holds on to itself as being true, did not come to the Hindus of the subcontinent

00:23:06.000 --> 00:23:07.600
[Guest]: as much as it came to the Muslims.

00:23:07.600 --> 00:23:08.600
[Amit Varma]: And that's not a bad thing.

00:23:08.600 --> 00:23:09.600
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

00:23:09.600 --> 00:23:13.120
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, through the course of this episode, we're going to talk about, you know, three

00:23:13.120 --> 00:23:16.320
[Amit Varma]: of the foundational thinkers who you're going to write about in your book as well, you are

00:23:16.320 --> 00:23:21.480
[Amit Varma]: writing about in your book as well, Savarkar, Golbarkar and Dindayal Upadhyay.

00:23:21.480 --> 00:23:28.800
[Amit Varma]: But before that, just place this, all of this in context for me, like, you could say that

00:23:28.800 --> 00:23:35.120
[Amit Varma]: in a sense, India is the only part of South Asia, which doesn't have something like a

00:23:35.120 --> 00:23:36.120
[Amit Varma]: Hindu Rashtra.

00:23:36.120 --> 00:23:38.920
[Guest]: Yeah, you're right.

00:23:38.920 --> 00:23:47.760
[Guest]: So all the states that comprise South Asia, except for India, are in some way a majoritarian.

00:23:47.760 --> 00:23:54.240
[Guest]: So Afghanistan, Pakistan chose to have Islamic constitutions, so did the Maldives.

00:23:54.240 --> 00:24:01.080
[Guest]: In Lanka, Buddhism is a privilege, according to the constitution.

00:24:01.080 --> 00:24:08.820
[Guest]: Bangladesh was part, obviously, of the Pakistan movement, but its foundational direction was

00:24:08.820 --> 00:24:09.820
[Guest]: secular.

00:24:09.820 --> 00:24:12.980
[Guest]: So it was Bengali nationalism rather than anything else.

00:24:12.980 --> 00:24:17.320
[Guest]: But when they became independent, they put Bismillah-e-Rahman-e-Rahim on top of the constitution,

00:24:17.320 --> 00:24:19.920
[Guest]: which was then removed by the court.

00:24:19.920 --> 00:24:24.480
[Guest]: But all the nations have dabbled in it in some way, Bhutan has a king who can only come

00:24:24.480 --> 00:24:31.320
[Guest]: from a particular faith, and he controls both the physical apparatus of the state as well

00:24:31.320 --> 00:24:34.440
[Guest]: as the spiritual one.

00:24:34.440 --> 00:24:39.040
[Guest]: Nepal used to be what is called a Hindu Rashtra till 2008.

00:24:39.040 --> 00:24:44.720
[Guest]: Though, of course, it was limited in the sense that you cannot have a Hindu Rashtra.

00:24:44.720 --> 00:24:49.360
[Guest]: And that's what my book is also about, it's not physically possible.

00:24:49.360 --> 00:24:56.600
[Guest]: But all of these states, at some point, assumed that they should be in some way a majoritarian,

00:24:56.600 --> 00:24:59.460
[Guest]: except for the largest country in South Asia.

00:24:59.460 --> 00:25:02.800
[Guest]: So we started off as being unique, and we've remained unique.

00:25:02.800 --> 00:25:08.840
[Guest]: I think both for reasons that were positive in nature, that the people who were writing

00:25:08.840 --> 00:25:12.280
[Guest]: the laws and the constitution felt it should be that way.

00:25:12.280 --> 00:25:17.800
[Guest]: And by default, that there is no real option for us to become majoritarian.

00:25:17.800 --> 00:25:21.600
[Amit Varma]: And it's interesting that you say that we remain that in two ways, one by, you know,

00:25:21.600 --> 00:25:26.360
[Amit Varma]: the elites who frame the constitution, obviously, and the other, by default, because, you know,

00:25:26.360 --> 00:25:30.440
[Amit Varma]: one of the thinkers, you're writing a book about Dindayal Upadhyay, often complained,

00:25:30.440 --> 00:25:34.480
[Amit Varma]: and I chatted about this in a previous episode with Shashi Tharoor, and Upadhyay used to

00:25:34.480 --> 00:25:40.560
[Amit Varma]: complain that our constitution is again, it's been imposed on us by a bunch of elites, and

00:25:40.560 --> 00:25:44.440
[Amit Varma]: it doesn't reflect the real India, therefore, perhaps implying that we need a constitution

00:25:44.440 --> 00:25:46.840
[Amit Varma]: that actually does.

00:25:46.840 --> 00:25:53.800
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, and when we sort of think about the last 70 years, I mean, obviously, elites

00:25:53.800 --> 00:25:57.800
[Amit Varma]: write constitutions everywhere, elites run policy, and they design the country.

00:25:57.800 --> 00:26:02.520
[Amit Varma]: But it seems that at some sense, what we see in the last five years, is also that there

00:26:02.520 --> 00:26:08.080
[Amit Varma]: is a sense of reassertion by people who are saying that no, this is a real India and you

00:26:08.080 --> 00:26:11.120
[Amit Varma]: elites have it wrong, and you're completely irrelevant.

00:26:11.120 --> 00:26:14.600
[Amit Varma]: And obviously, a side note to that is all the ranting that goes on against the elites

00:26:14.600 --> 00:26:18.240
[Amit Varma]: and how the word liberal has become a pejorative and so on.

00:26:18.240 --> 00:26:23.080
[Amit Varma]: But what do you feel about something that I consider a paradox, being a liberal of sorts

00:26:23.080 --> 00:26:30.240
[Amit Varma]: myself, that you had a bunch of liberal elites imposing a liberal constitution on an illiberal

00:26:30.240 --> 00:26:31.240
[Amit Varma]: country.

00:26:31.240 --> 00:26:35.480
[Amit Varma]: So how can that imposition be liberal in itself?

00:26:35.480 --> 00:26:38.640
[Guest]: I think it's a very good question.

00:26:38.640 --> 00:26:40.440
[Guest]: So there are two parts to it.

00:26:40.440 --> 00:26:50.320
[Guest]: One is the assumption made by people like Upadhyay and others that in some way, the

00:26:50.320 --> 00:26:55.280
[Guest]: constitution represents values that are foreign or that are alien.

00:26:55.280 --> 00:27:00.640
[Guest]: I haven't ever found a response to what else it should be.

00:27:00.640 --> 00:27:05.720
[Guest]: Okay, I accept the fact that the Constituent Assembly of India is basically the Congress

00:27:05.720 --> 00:27:11.000
[Guest]: Party debating itself, there's no particularly strong representation from what we would consider

00:27:11.000 --> 00:27:16.360
[Guest]: to be conservative, upper caste elements, exerting that sort of, you know, conservatism

00:27:16.360 --> 00:27:17.400
[Guest]: from the Hindu faith.

00:27:17.400 --> 00:27:19.800
[Guest]: But if they were, what would they do?

00:27:19.800 --> 00:27:30.160
[Guest]: The problem with the majoritarian Hindutva aspect is that, unlike Islam, where you can

00:27:30.160 --> 00:27:38.080
[Guest]: have a majoritarian constitution that discriminates against the minorities, and you do have that

00:27:38.080 --> 00:27:41.720
[Guest]: in a lot of places, including in Pakistan.

00:27:41.720 --> 00:27:48.040
[Guest]: Problem with Hindutva constitution, the way that I have understood it based on what I've

00:27:48.040 --> 00:27:53.520
[Guest]: read, is that it will discriminate against most Hindus.

00:27:53.520 --> 00:28:00.140
[Guest]: If we look at the caste system, there are two things that any state can do when it decides

00:28:00.140 --> 00:28:05.360
[Guest]: to be a majoritarian from the faith perspective.

00:28:05.360 --> 00:28:09.400
[Guest]: One is that it tries to impose the articles of its faith.

00:28:09.400 --> 00:28:11.840
[Guest]: The other is that it discriminates.

00:28:11.840 --> 00:28:14.080
[Guest]: We've got the latter, and we've had it for a long time.

00:28:14.080 --> 00:28:19.640
[Guest]: I don't think that it's the BJP that has done bad things by itself, and the people that

00:28:19.640 --> 00:28:22.080
[Guest]: came before it were in some way different.

00:28:22.080 --> 00:28:28.960
[Guest]: They were different in minor ways, but I think that for the most part, it's not that we were

00:28:28.960 --> 00:28:33.800
[Guest]: going through a kind of halcyon phase, and then it's suddenly become hell.

00:28:33.800 --> 00:28:35.440
[Guest]: That's not the way that I see it.

00:28:35.440 --> 00:28:40.440
[Guest]: The problem is on the other side, Pakistan can say through its constitution, and it has

00:28:40.440 --> 00:28:47.120
[Guest]: said that no non-Muslim can become the president, and they can't, because that's what the law

00:28:47.120 --> 00:28:48.120
[Guest]: says.

00:28:48.120 --> 00:28:56.920
[Guest]: How is it that we are going to impose the Hindu faith on a population that's 85% Hindu,

00:28:56.920 --> 00:29:04.560
[Guest]: where you've got a third of that population is Dalit and Adivasi, about 50% is from the

00:29:04.560 --> 00:29:10.840
[Guest]: community I come from, which is Shudra, based on the Smritis.

00:29:10.840 --> 00:29:11.960
[Guest]: As is Modi himself.

00:29:11.960 --> 00:29:15.880
[Guest]: As is Modi himself.

00:29:15.880 --> 00:29:20.780
[Guest]: Imposing the articles of faith would lead to wholesale discrimination against the majority

00:29:20.780 --> 00:29:22.120
[Guest]: of Hindus.

00:29:22.120 --> 00:29:26.320
[Guest]: And so it's not physically possible for us to have Hindu Rashtra in this country.

00:29:26.320 --> 00:29:30.080
[Amit Varma]: I think if I may take a stab at answering the rhetorical question, one of the things

00:29:30.080 --> 00:29:33.860
[Amit Varma]: that our constitution aims to do and doesn't do well enough, in my opinion, in the sense

00:29:33.860 --> 00:29:37.920
[Amit Varma]: that it's not liberal enough, therefore, is focus on protecting individual rights, which

00:29:37.920 --> 00:29:41.840
[Amit Varma]: it doesn't do completely enough, but it does to enough of an extent that you can call it

00:29:41.840 --> 00:29:43.600
[Amit Varma]: a liberal constitution.

00:29:43.600 --> 00:29:47.320
[Amit Varma]: And you know, as you pointed out in the notes that you sent me from your book about this,

00:29:47.320 --> 00:29:51.320
[Amit Varma]: that this was something specifically that, not in the context of the constitution, but

00:29:51.320 --> 00:29:55.120
[Amit Varma]: in terms of what a Hindu Rashtra should look like, that Golwalkar felt that there should

00:29:55.120 --> 00:30:00.800
[Amit Varma]: be no focus on individual rights at all, that the collective took precedence over the individual.

00:30:00.800 --> 00:30:05.520
[Amit Varma]: So if I would imagine a Hindutva constitution, and obviously I can't because I don't have

00:30:05.520 --> 00:30:09.320
[Amit Varma]: the kind of knowledge that you do, but if I were to imagine it, I imagine one of the

00:30:09.320 --> 00:30:14.920
[Amit Varma]: things that it would not do, which the current constitution does partially, is protect individual

00:30:14.920 --> 00:30:15.920
[Guest]: rights.

00:30:15.920 --> 00:30:19.320
[Guest]: Maybe that's a good way of looking at it, that you would have collective rights, but

00:30:19.320 --> 00:30:21.360
[Guest]: what would that look like in law?

00:30:21.360 --> 00:30:26.280
[Guest]: Would we always act in concert as a mob in terms of, would we never have a disagreement

00:30:26.280 --> 00:30:30.880
[Guest]: within that specific schism that we would have, whether it would be Vaishnavs or you

00:30:30.880 --> 00:30:31.880
[Amit Varma]: know, whatever else?

00:30:31.880 --> 00:30:35.280
[Amit Varma]: I guess it would have far lesser protections for women, for example, to start with.

00:30:35.280 --> 00:30:36.280
[Guest]: Yeah.

00:30:36.280 --> 00:30:39.680
[Guest]: And I think that that's probably what, what we are living through, that you're living

00:30:39.680 --> 00:30:44.760
[Guest]: through a default Hindu Rashtra that discriminates against say, women going to temple because

00:30:44.760 --> 00:30:52.560
[Guest]: they are seen as, you know, impure in some way, in terms of a practice, but that runs

00:30:52.560 --> 00:30:53.560
[Guest]: into law.

00:30:53.560 --> 00:30:59.120
[Guest]: The law says, I'm sorry, but you know, if you have a constitution that says equality,

00:30:59.120 --> 00:31:05.240
[Guest]: and I think we have a pretty mediocre set of judges in our Supreme Court, but even there,

00:31:05.240 --> 00:31:11.720
[Guest]: I think you would find that when the practice of sort of Hindu Rashtra runs into the constitution,

00:31:11.720 --> 00:31:20.120
[Guest]: the response is usually incoherent, that it is not able to express itself because the

00:31:20.120 --> 00:31:26.600
[Guest]: discrimination is underneath rather than completely externalized, like it is in Islam.

00:31:26.600 --> 00:31:33.120
[Amit Varma]: And one of the things that you said when we were chatting about this episode was that

00:31:33.120 --> 00:31:37.440
[Amit Varma]: we need to, if you're talking about the Hindu Rashtra, we also need to talk about the Pakistan

00:31:37.440 --> 00:31:42.320
[Amit Varma]: project and what happened there and how that played out as an example of a majoritarian

00:31:42.320 --> 00:31:46.720
[Amit Varma]: sort of state, our immediate neighbor, and I mean, we are practically the same country

00:31:46.720 --> 00:31:47.720
[Amit Varma]: until recently.

00:31:47.720 --> 00:31:51.200
[Guest]: Tell me a little bit about that.

00:31:51.200 --> 00:31:53.960
[Guest]: Pakistan can be seen in a few different ways.

00:31:53.960 --> 00:31:58.240
[Guest]: So I think the one thing that I came to learn pretty late in life was that the partition

00:31:58.240 --> 00:32:04.440
[Guest]: of India was basically the partition of just two states, Bengal and Punjab.

00:32:04.440 --> 00:32:12.600
[Guest]: And on the West, the transfer of citizens was almost absolute.

00:32:12.600 --> 00:32:19.880
[Guest]: So very few non-Muslims remaining in West Punjab, very few Muslims remaining in East

00:32:19.880 --> 00:32:21.880
[Guest]: Punjab.

00:32:21.880 --> 00:32:33.440
[Guest]: Secondly, and I know this because of the work done by the amateur sociologists and ethnographers

00:32:33.440 --> 00:32:38.280
[Guest]: that the Raj brought with it, who were really interested in communities and they would document

00:32:38.280 --> 00:32:39.680
[Guest]: stuff.

00:32:39.680 --> 00:32:47.440
[Guest]: What happened in Punjab was that the conversion of the primary mercantile castes, there were

00:32:47.440 --> 00:32:55.720
[Guest]: two of them, Khatri and Amaroda, other than the Baniyas, who were very small, did not

00:32:55.720 --> 00:32:58.160
[Guest]: happen outside of Sikhism.

00:32:58.160 --> 00:33:08.080
[Guest]: So 99.9% of the people from these two communities remained Hindu or they were Sikh.

00:33:08.080 --> 00:33:13.720
[Guest]: The 10 Sikh gurus were Khatri.

00:33:13.720 --> 00:33:20.440
[Guest]: Partition on that front was a partition also of castes because of this, that you had a

00:33:20.440 --> 00:33:31.520
[Guest]: fairly talented set of merchants who all moved after 47.

00:33:31.520 --> 00:33:39.320
[Guest]: And you had, on the other hand, a very hardworking set of Jats who had been given access by the

00:33:39.320 --> 00:33:41.600
[Guest]: British to the army.

00:33:41.600 --> 00:33:48.760
[Guest]: After the mutiny, they were the Balwak of the British Indian army.

00:33:48.760 --> 00:33:50.760
[Guest]: And they had been given lands and so on.

00:33:50.760 --> 00:33:54.840
[Guest]: So you've got this fairly martial population in charge of a large part of Pakistan, more

00:33:54.840 --> 00:34:02.840
[Guest]: than 50% of what is today Pakistan and what used to be West Pakistan is Punjabi speaking.

00:34:02.840 --> 00:34:10.960
[Guest]: So you had a dominant martial caste there in charge of the population without the leavening

00:34:10.960 --> 00:34:16.620
[Guest]: of the mercantilism of the Khatri and the Arora Punjabis.

00:34:16.620 --> 00:34:24.080
[Guest]: To my mind that had a significant effect in the way that the country evolved and has continued

00:34:24.080 --> 00:34:25.080
[Guest]: to evolve.

00:34:25.080 --> 00:34:29.480
[Guest]: I think the militaristic spirit that it shows, the love of the army despite being ruled by

00:34:29.480 --> 00:34:35.680
[Guest]: it for most of its post-1947 period speaks to that.

00:34:35.680 --> 00:34:44.480
[Guest]: I think there is some romance to the way that they view the military.

00:34:44.480 --> 00:34:51.800
[Guest]: The Pakistan project, I think, collapsed from the modernist point of view with the death

00:34:51.800 --> 00:34:57.200
[Guest]: of Jinnah where in his person, there was still some hope that they were going to some kind

00:34:57.200 --> 00:35:00.800
[Guest]: of Turkey type state which would.

00:35:00.800 --> 00:35:07.100
[Guest]: So Turkey in the 20s, romanized the alphabet, banned the fairs.

00:35:07.100 --> 00:35:12.880
[Guest]: And so that was seen as a sign of modernity and there were suits and they had guns and

00:35:12.880 --> 00:35:13.880
[Guest]: so on.

00:35:13.880 --> 00:35:17.120
[Guest]: And Jinnah was quite sort of enamored of Hamata Turk.

00:35:17.120 --> 00:35:18.560
[Guest]: He's named only two books that he's read.

00:35:18.560 --> 00:35:24.760
[Guest]: I translated a very short interview he did in Gujarati in the 1920s.

00:35:24.760 --> 00:35:30.320
[Guest]: And the two books that he's read, one is The Count of Monte Cristo and the other is a book

00:35:30.320 --> 00:35:32.840
[Guest]: called A Gray Wolf by this man called H.C.

00:35:32.840 --> 00:35:37.400
[Guest]: Armstrong who had profiled Kamala Tatuk.

00:35:37.400 --> 00:35:39.000
[Guest]: Were these his favorite books or do you think they were?

00:35:39.000 --> 00:35:40.360
[Guest]: I don't think he was well read.

00:35:40.360 --> 00:35:42.280
[Guest]: He's a beautiful writer.

00:35:42.280 --> 00:35:46.240
[Guest]: I wish I hadn't spent as much money on the Jinnah papers as I have because they're rubbish.

00:35:46.240 --> 00:35:53.040
[Guest]: But his, the way that he spoke and wrote is manifestly superior to what people of my generation

00:35:53.040 --> 00:35:57.720
[Guest]: who've studied English and you know, we are not there.

00:35:57.720 --> 00:35:59.800
[Guest]: He spoke and wrote it really well.

00:35:59.800 --> 00:36:02.800
[Guest]: He had a sort of felicity for the language.

00:36:02.800 --> 00:36:04.480
[Guest]: And he was an accomplished lawyer.

00:36:04.480 --> 00:36:06.000
[Guest]: He was a very good advocate.

00:36:06.000 --> 00:36:07.480
[Guest]: He was not a particularly good lawyer.

00:36:07.480 --> 00:36:12.200
[Guest]: I think the difference in that is that he was very good at taking a brief and then being

00:36:12.200 --> 00:36:17.400
[Guest]: able to represent it before a judge rather than doing the hard work of finding the details

00:36:17.400 --> 00:36:18.400
[Guest]: out and so on.

00:36:18.400 --> 00:36:22.840
[Guest]: So he was seen as a phenomenal advocate, but not that good a lawyer.

00:36:22.840 --> 00:36:27.840
[Guest]: So he dies a few months after partition as does Gandhi.

00:36:27.840 --> 00:36:36.000
[Guest]: And in the weeks up to partition, Jinnah has made statements that suggest that the constitution

00:36:36.000 --> 00:36:40.280
[Guest]: of Pakistan, he's careful to say that it is the work of the constituent assembly and not

00:36:40.280 --> 00:36:42.080
[Guest]: his own.

00:36:42.080 --> 00:36:47.320
[Guest]: But he says enough to suggest that it would have some sort of alignment with the faith.

00:36:47.320 --> 00:36:53.400
[Guest]: Then just four days before partition, he gives a speech to the, he speaks to the constituent

00:36:53.400 --> 00:37:01.760
[Guest]: assembly where he says things like in a post-independence Pakistan, Hindus will be free to go to their

00:37:01.760 --> 00:37:02.800
[Guest]: temples and so on.

00:37:02.800 --> 00:37:06.840
[Guest]: And he says that the state is not likely at some point in the future to look on citizens

00:37:06.840 --> 00:37:10.440
[Guest]: through the prism of faith, that they will just be Pakistanis.

00:37:10.440 --> 00:37:14.480
[Guest]: So that suggested to people later that he was trying to speak of a secular state, but

00:37:14.480 --> 00:37:17.240
[Guest]: he never used that word secular.

00:37:17.240 --> 00:37:25.800
[Guest]: And he left enough sort of evidence here and there for us to assume that he would be okay

00:37:25.800 --> 00:37:29.200
[Guest]: with the way that the Pakistani constitution, constitutions, I should say they have three

00:37:29.200 --> 00:37:33.440
[Guest]: of them turned out.

00:37:33.440 --> 00:37:39.800
[Guest]: And but he dies, he's got TB just before a partition, his doctor who's a Parsi man from

00:37:39.800 --> 00:37:43.040
[Guest]: Bombay doesn't tell anybody.

00:37:43.040 --> 00:37:48.280
[Guest]: And six months after he dies, the Pakistani constituent assembly, which has a fairly large

00:37:48.280 --> 00:37:56.240
[Guest]: composition of Bengali Hindus from East Pakistan, debate, they start their discussions on what

00:37:56.240 --> 00:37:59.400
[Guest]: the constitution should be.

00:37:59.400 --> 00:38:10.360
[Guest]: And Liaquat Ali Khan, who's this North Indian kind of royalty type figure, Sunni, Jinnah

00:38:10.360 --> 00:38:17.480
[Guest]: was a Gujarati from a very small community called the Seven Arshiyas, the Khojas.

00:38:17.480 --> 00:38:24.920
[Guest]: And he had actually converted out of it at one point.

00:38:24.920 --> 00:38:33.440
[Guest]: Liaquat proposed something called the objective resolution, which was a sort of a preamble.

00:38:33.440 --> 00:38:41.400
[Guest]: And Pakistan, according to that, a preamble would be an Islamic state, where sovereignty

00:38:41.400 --> 00:38:44.200
[Guest]: belonged to Allah.

00:38:44.200 --> 00:38:49.200
[Guest]: But it would be given interest to the people of Pakistan.

00:38:49.200 --> 00:38:54.440
[Guest]: And you would have democracy, you would have freedom, you would have tolerance, you would

00:38:54.440 --> 00:38:57.400
[Guest]: have justice, you would have all of that.

00:38:57.400 --> 00:39:02.520
[Guest]: But you would have all of these as enunciated by Islam.

00:39:02.520 --> 00:39:07.960
[Guest]: And this naturally alarmed the Hindus in the Pakistani constituent assembly.

00:39:07.960 --> 00:39:14.080
[Guest]: And there's a series of very learned interventions that they made.

00:39:14.080 --> 00:39:15.480
[Guest]: And it's worth reading them.

00:39:15.480 --> 00:39:20.080
[Guest]: And I hope to reproduce much of that in my book.

00:39:20.080 --> 00:39:24.140
[Guest]: Saying that this was not what Jinnah had promised, that this was vague, they were going into

00:39:24.140 --> 00:39:27.680
[Guest]: a space which no other nation had gone through before.

00:39:27.680 --> 00:39:33.280
[Guest]: Pakistan and Israel pretty much at the same time determined that they're going to be states

00:39:33.280 --> 00:39:37.640
[Guest]: that have a faith based component in the constitution.

00:39:37.640 --> 00:39:42.560
[Guest]: So Jewish state there and you've got the Muslim state here.

00:39:42.560 --> 00:39:52.840
[Guest]: But these words as enunciated by Islam didn't really mean much specifically.

00:39:52.840 --> 00:39:57.160
[Guest]: Islam itself broke into two right at the beginning.

00:39:57.160 --> 00:40:01.920
[Guest]: Not because of a theological dispute, but because of a political dispute who should

00:40:01.920 --> 00:40:04.520
[Guest]: succeed the prophet.

00:40:04.520 --> 00:40:12.800
[Guest]: And so there was no real means of saying what Islamic democracy was, what was Islamic equality.

00:40:12.800 --> 00:40:20.760
[Guest]: Being a desert people, they had the primary form of asset with the family was actually

00:40:20.760 --> 00:40:23.960
[Guest]: cattle, easy to divide.

00:40:23.960 --> 00:40:30.360
[Guest]: And so at a time in the world, 1400 years ago, when women did not have much by way of

00:40:30.360 --> 00:40:37.440
[Guest]: rights, the Prophet of Islam said that a daughter should inherit one half of what the son gets.

00:40:37.440 --> 00:40:42.140
[Guest]: And this was great for that time, but you can't have the same law after 1400 years.

00:40:42.140 --> 00:40:49.760
[Guest]: What happened was in the interpretations that they gave these very basic sentences, Pakistan

00:40:49.760 --> 00:40:51.960
[Guest]: applied them across law.

00:40:51.960 --> 00:40:55.840
[Guest]: So Pakistan started off and it still has the same IPC that we do.

00:40:55.840 --> 00:41:00.720
[Guest]: So they know what 420 means, for example, they know what 153A means.

00:41:00.720 --> 00:41:05.320
[Guest]: Or 124A sedition is right there.

00:41:05.320 --> 00:41:10.160
[Guest]: They've tweaked some of the punishments to make them harsher, especially for blasphemy

00:41:10.160 --> 00:41:12.560
[Guest]: in the 80s.

00:41:12.560 --> 00:41:18.160
[Guest]: But so they started off with the same laws, but they thought that they should Islamize

00:41:18.160 --> 00:41:19.400
[Guest]: the state in some way.

00:41:19.400 --> 00:41:27.200
[Guest]: And one way of doing that was to try and use a precepts and use some statements from 1400

00:41:27.200 --> 00:41:32.240
[Guest]: years ago and try and apply them to the modern world, which doesn't work.

00:41:32.240 --> 00:41:37.320
[Guest]: So they had this constitution that came out in the 50s.

00:41:37.320 --> 00:41:43.440
[Guest]: Almost immediately, the army took over and kept power for a decade.

00:41:43.440 --> 00:41:46.800
[Guest]: The army had its own constitution.

00:41:46.800 --> 00:41:53.240
[Guest]: The army was tough on East Pakistan, Jinnah wanted to impose Urdu on the whole, he didn't

00:41:53.240 --> 00:41:55.920
[Guest]: speak it himself, couldn't read it.

00:41:55.920 --> 00:41:59.440
[Guest]: He spoke Gujarati and he spoke it really well.

00:41:59.440 --> 00:42:02.760
[Guest]: I've translated that interview that I told you about.

00:42:02.760 --> 00:42:06.920
[Guest]: His writing is really polished and he knows the language.

00:42:06.920 --> 00:42:11.440
[Guest]: And I'm sure being in South Bombay, the tough that he was, that would have been the primary

00:42:11.440 --> 00:42:15.360
[Guest]: language even in court for many decades after a partition.

00:42:15.360 --> 00:42:21.560
[Guest]: If you look at lawyers like Chagla or whoever else, a lot of the heavyweights in the Indian

00:42:21.560 --> 00:42:28.280
[Guest]: judiciary were Parsis, Muslims, Hindus who came out of the Bombay High Court.

00:42:28.280 --> 00:42:35.040
[Guest]: So they tried to adapt to a modern constitution, things that they believe they should be doing

00:42:35.040 --> 00:42:37.040
[Guest]: out of a sense of piety.

00:42:37.040 --> 00:42:39.680
[Guest]: Nobody's doing this to persecute people.

00:42:39.680 --> 00:42:47.480
[Guest]: The fact is that when they wrote the objectives resolution, the Muslims were probably confident

00:42:47.480 --> 00:42:53.120
[Guest]: that they were not going to produce a state that was going to in any way discriminate.

00:42:53.120 --> 00:42:54.720
[Guest]: But that is what it did.

00:42:54.720 --> 00:42:56.000
[Guest]: And they were never happy with it.

00:42:56.000 --> 00:43:03.320
[Guest]: The problem is with a utopian state or a constitution that aims to take you to a state that is in

00:43:03.320 --> 00:43:06.080
[Guest]: some way a utopia.

00:43:06.080 --> 00:43:07.080
[Guest]: It never works.

00:43:07.080 --> 00:43:12.440
[Guest]: So Pakistan had to go through one constitution in the 50s, another one in the 60s.

00:43:12.440 --> 00:43:13.440
[Guest]: The country broke.

00:43:13.440 --> 00:43:18.120
[Guest]: I was talking about Jinnah wanting to impose this language on the Bangladeshis, which they

00:43:18.120 --> 00:43:19.120
[Guest]: didn't want.

00:43:19.120 --> 00:43:22.160
[Guest]: And there were more of them, in fact, there were more of them.

00:43:22.160 --> 00:43:28.640
[Guest]: And if things remain the way they are, for the first time in the history of the subcontinent,

00:43:28.640 --> 00:43:34.440
[Guest]: in two or three years, the Bangladesh per capita income will outstrip that of Pakistan,

00:43:34.440 --> 00:43:37.640
[Guest]: which is remarkable for a country that was thought to be a basket case only 40 years

00:43:37.640 --> 00:43:38.640
[Guest]: ago.

00:43:38.640 --> 00:43:45.160
[Guest]: So Bangladesh secedes with help from India and the country breaks up.

00:43:45.160 --> 00:43:52.040
[Guest]: And there's a third constitution, 1973, written by the PPP under Bhutto.

00:43:52.040 --> 00:43:55.320
[Guest]: And that's the one that's remained in some form today.

00:43:55.320 --> 00:43:58.080
[Guest]: But over time, the discrimination has been written in.

00:43:58.080 --> 00:44:04.520
[Guest]: So you've got, for example, no president or prime minister can be a non-Muslim.

00:44:04.520 --> 00:44:15.360
[Guest]: You've got the law on a property, Zia ul Haq comes and extends that to rape.

00:44:15.360 --> 00:44:19.640
[Guest]: So a woman's testimony is seen to be worth only half a man's.

00:44:19.640 --> 00:44:25.240
[Guest]: And if a man is accused of rape by a woman, she must produce two male witnesses to the

00:44:25.240 --> 00:44:26.240
[Guest]: act of rape.

00:44:26.240 --> 00:44:30.320
[Guest]: And if she cannot do that, she's accused of fornication and jailed.

00:44:30.320 --> 00:44:32.920
[Guest]: And this is what actually happened.

00:44:32.920 --> 00:44:36.600
[Guest]: No party was able to escape it once it came on to the books.

00:44:36.600 --> 00:44:42.960
[Guest]: Once you had a written constitution that demanded that the faith be in some way imposed so that

00:44:42.960 --> 00:44:48.080
[Guest]: people could benefit from the blessings of living in a faithful country.

00:44:48.080 --> 00:44:49.080
[Guest]: It didn't stop.

00:44:49.080 --> 00:44:51.400
[Guest]: The PPP was a liberal socialist parties.

00:44:51.400 --> 00:44:56.680
[Guest]: They are the ones that changed the constitution in 1974.

00:44:56.680 --> 00:45:02.840
[Guest]: The Bhutto apostatized this community called the Ahmadis.

00:45:02.840 --> 00:45:11.000
[Guest]: And even today, Pakistani passport holders must, in writing, disown membership of that

00:45:11.000 --> 00:45:12.000
[Guest]: community.

00:45:12.000 --> 00:45:13.000
[Guest]: Why?

00:45:13.000 --> 00:45:15.800
[Guest]: There was a riot in the 50s.

00:45:15.800 --> 00:45:19.280
[Guest]: This is a community that comes out of Punjab.

00:45:19.280 --> 00:45:24.040
[Guest]: There are many of them here in India as well.

00:45:24.040 --> 00:45:31.960
[Guest]: So we think of Islam in India as being sort of very monotheistic, but it's not really

00:45:31.960 --> 00:45:32.960
[Guest]: that.

00:45:32.960 --> 00:45:39.360
[Guest]: There's lots of saints, just like St. Paul came and converted the polytheistic Romans

00:45:39.360 --> 00:45:42.600
[Guest]: into Christians by giving them saints, you know, you could go and worship whoever you

00:45:42.600 --> 00:45:49.000
[Guest]: wanted to, but you would now call them a saint and they would be a sort of intercessor between

00:45:49.000 --> 00:45:51.600
[Guest]: you and God.

00:45:51.600 --> 00:45:53.260
[Guest]: Islam's done the same thing.

00:45:53.260 --> 00:46:02.680
[Guest]: More people pray at shrines in Lahore or in Ajmer than have ever gone to Mecca.

00:46:02.680 --> 00:46:03.680
[Guest]: And that's the way it is.

00:46:03.680 --> 00:46:05.400
[Guest]: That is the subcontinent's faith.

00:46:05.400 --> 00:46:11.920
[Guest]: It's very powerfully colored with mysticism and the power of dead people.

00:46:11.920 --> 00:46:22.520
[Guest]: So one of these sects in Punjab, one of these men has visions and Islam has been quite firm

00:46:22.520 --> 00:46:29.880
[Guest]: in its belief that Muhammad is the last of the line of prophets that starts with Adam,

00:46:29.880 --> 00:46:32.200
[Guest]: that he's the first and he's the last.

00:46:32.200 --> 00:46:36.680
[Guest]: And anyone having visions then becomes a sort of threat.

00:46:36.680 --> 00:46:42.360
[Guest]: And therefore, there was some problem with the, it's a fairly recent community, it's

00:46:42.360 --> 00:46:45.440
[Guest]: not that old, late 19th century, I think.

00:46:45.440 --> 00:46:51.440
[Guest]: There were some riots in Pakistani Punjab in the 50s on the same issue.

00:46:51.440 --> 00:46:56.800
[Guest]: And then rather than surrender the street to mobs that wanted violence on this, Bhutto

00:46:56.800 --> 00:47:01.960
[Guest]: just sort of did the easy thing and rewrote the law.

00:47:01.960 --> 00:47:04.720
[Guest]: That's happened in a lot of places with the blasphemy law.

00:47:04.720 --> 00:47:11.680
[Guest]: So as I said, Pakistan's got exactly the same set of laws that we have written by Macaulay

00:47:11.680 --> 00:47:14.160
[Guest]: in the 1860s.

00:47:14.160 --> 00:47:19.400
[Guest]: And blasphemy was punishable by up to three years in jail.

00:47:19.400 --> 00:47:20.400
[Guest]: Almost nobody blasphemed.

00:47:20.400 --> 00:47:30.880
[Guest]: There were only eight cases of blasphemy registered before 1980 in India and Pakistan combined

00:47:30.880 --> 00:47:34.660
[Guest]: for a law that's like more than a hundred years old.

00:47:34.660 --> 00:47:36.920
[Guest]: So it's not that kind of place.

00:47:36.920 --> 00:47:41.480
[Guest]: I think the veneration of faith is very high in our part.

00:47:41.480 --> 00:47:46.280
[Guest]: So it's very unlikely that you'll find somebody deliberately blaspheming.

00:47:46.280 --> 00:47:48.520
[Guest]: And the judiciary was quite tolerant.

00:47:48.520 --> 00:47:54.760
[Guest]: So when you had somebody like Naikar in the South breaking idols of Ganesha in public,

00:47:54.760 --> 00:47:57.560
[Guest]: it was seen as something that he had the right to do.

00:47:57.560 --> 00:48:01.080
[Guest]: We can't do it anymore, obviously, in this country.

00:48:01.080 --> 00:48:06.880
[Guest]: But in Pakistan, what happened was they changed it to death, immediately the number of cases

00:48:06.880 --> 00:48:11.400
[Guest]: of blasphemy, especially against non-Muslims shot up to over a thousand.

00:48:11.400 --> 00:48:16.440
[Guest]: It was a tool to be used against people you didn't like for whatever reason, it could

00:48:16.440 --> 00:48:21.600
[Guest]: be reasons of faith, it could be reasons of property, which it often was.

00:48:21.600 --> 00:48:25.400
[Guest]: But it gave the law, the anger of society.

00:48:25.400 --> 00:48:30.360
[Guest]: And I think that that's what usually happens when you have a majoritarian state in South

00:48:30.360 --> 00:48:36.200
[Guest]: Asia, that there is an undercurrent, and it becomes more powerful.

00:48:36.200 --> 00:48:40.940
[Guest]: And it expresses itself through violence, when you turn it into law.

00:48:40.940 --> 00:48:47.800
[Amit Varma]: So is the whole Pakistan project, a cautionary tale of sorts for those in India who see the

00:48:47.800 --> 00:48:49.360
[Guest]: specter of a Hindu rush?

00:48:49.360 --> 00:48:50.360
[Guest]: I think so.

00:48:50.360 --> 00:48:56.640
[Guest]: I think that we ought to look at where majoritarianism took Pakistan, not just from the point of

00:48:56.640 --> 00:48:58.080
[Guest]: view of the constitution.

00:48:58.080 --> 00:49:02.300
[Guest]: Like I said, they're on the third constitution or fifth, if you really look at it, the kind

00:49:02.300 --> 00:49:06.040
[Guest]: of mauling that Zia did in the 80s.

00:49:06.040 --> 00:49:14.200
[Guest]: And then you know, you had people like Musharraf, who was there for almost a decade.

00:49:14.200 --> 00:49:15.760
[Guest]: Nothing good comes of it.

00:49:15.760 --> 00:49:22.880
[Guest]: The idea that our constitution is in some way foreign, or the values that it talks about

00:49:22.880 --> 00:49:28.720
[Guest]: equality, or secularism, or whatever is foreign is bogus.

00:49:28.720 --> 00:49:32.160
[Guest]: And these are not values that are owned by any one nation or any one race.

00:49:32.160 --> 00:49:36.600
[Amit Varma]: I mean, my point is, even if they say originated with the Enlightenment and came to us from

00:49:36.600 --> 00:49:38.160
[Amit Varma]: there, what difference does it make now?

00:49:38.160 --> 00:49:39.160
[Guest]: It does make a difference.

00:49:39.160 --> 00:49:48.840
[Guest]: You know, the Greeks really respected India, Pythagoras, who they credit as being the origin

00:49:48.840 --> 00:49:55.800
[Guest]: of the seven note scale in music, and you know, we are familiar with the theorem, was

00:49:55.800 --> 00:49:59.640
[Guest]: actually a vegetarian because he came to India and picked it up with him.

00:49:59.640 --> 00:50:00.640
[Guest]: That's what the Greeks believe.

00:50:00.640 --> 00:50:04.440
[Guest]: This is not something that this is not a Tejo Mahalai kind of thing, you know, if you read

00:50:04.440 --> 00:50:10.480
[Guest]: Plato and Socrates and from that period, immense respect for what the East had.

00:50:10.480 --> 00:50:14.560
[Guest]: And I don't think there is any one moment in history where any one community or nation

00:50:14.560 --> 00:50:20.040
[Guest]: says that we've, you know, put this up from zero, democracy is just a word.

00:50:20.040 --> 00:50:24.000
[Guest]: But I'm saying that if you are going to lead a group of people, there's going to be pushback

00:50:24.000 --> 00:50:26.640
[Guest]: from that group, they would want a stake in power.

00:50:26.640 --> 00:50:30.440
[Guest]: That's the way the human being is, we're not the sort of people who can be herded into

