[Amit Varma]: Welcome back to the scene in the unseen.

00:52:24.080 --> 00:52:29.040
[Amit Varma]: I'm chatting with Aakar Patel about his forthcoming book on the Hindu Rashtra by which I guess

00:52:29.040 --> 00:52:31.680
[Amit Varma]: in a sense you mean Hindutva.

00:52:31.680 --> 00:52:36.920
[Amit Varma]: And that's again a term coined by Vinayak Savarkar, you know, the first of the thinkers

00:52:36.920 --> 00:52:37.920
[Guest]: you focus on.

00:52:37.920 --> 00:52:38.920
[Guest]: Yeah, it's a new word.

00:52:38.920 --> 00:52:46.400
[Guest]: I don't think it occurs in the Smritis, it doesn't occur in the Vedas, there's no reference

00:52:46.400 --> 00:52:47.520
[Guest]: to it.

00:52:47.520 --> 00:52:56.480
[Guest]: But the community of people who are Hindutva followers are very possessive about that word.

00:52:56.480 --> 00:52:57.840
[Guest]: Savarkar definitely was.

00:52:57.840 --> 00:53:04.600
[Guest]: He was very keen to show that its origins were not in some way Muslim in nature.

00:53:04.600 --> 00:53:09.120
[Guest]: This might have been a debate when he was writing the book in the 20s, certainly it's

00:53:09.120 --> 00:53:10.880
[Guest]: not now.

00:53:10.880 --> 00:53:17.880
[Guest]: But he felt that the Hindu faith ought to own the word and the etymology of the word

00:53:17.880 --> 00:53:21.600
[Guest]: from Sindhu and so on.

00:53:21.600 --> 00:53:29.520
[Guest]: So we don't have any particular references to Hindutva till he writes his book in the

00:53:29.520 --> 00:53:30.520
[Guest]: 20s.

00:53:30.520 --> 00:53:38.160
[Guest]: He's a young man at that point, he's in jail and this is still pre-1947 India.

00:53:38.160 --> 00:53:44.200
[Guest]: So his concern is not what the relationship of the state is with Hindutva.

00:53:44.200 --> 00:53:45.200
[Guest]: That is not his concern.

00:53:45.200 --> 00:53:55.360
[Guest]: I think his primary objective is to his definition and he's trying to construct a nation which

00:53:55.360 --> 00:53:58.800
[Guest]: is whole, which is intact and which is pure.

00:53:58.800 --> 00:54:04.640
[Guest]: And he finds that idea in the word Hindu, which to him means two things.

00:54:04.640 --> 00:54:14.480
[Guest]: It means the land in which the Hindus live, beginning at the Indus and moving east.

00:54:14.480 --> 00:54:19.040
[Guest]: And secondly, what he calls the faiths that are of this land.

00:54:19.040 --> 00:54:26.800
[Guest]: So he includes Jainism, he includes Sikhism, includes Buddhism.

00:54:26.800 --> 00:54:34.360
[Guest]: He excludes Islam, excludes Christianity, but includes atheists who are Hindu.

00:54:34.360 --> 00:54:38.720
[Guest]: So maybe he hasn't thought it through fully, but there are some contradictions there that

00:54:38.720 --> 00:54:40.560
[Guest]: remain.

00:54:40.560 --> 00:54:45.140
[Guest]: But his idea was to develop a theory of nationhood.

00:54:45.140 --> 00:54:50.160
[Guest]: This is a period when Europe's going through a lot of that sort of thinking itself.

00:54:50.160 --> 00:54:54.040
[Guest]: And he arrives at this construct, which he calls Hindutva.

00:54:54.040 --> 00:54:58.040
[Amit Varma]: And in fact, reading his book, it struck me that more than half of it seemed to be about

00:54:58.040 --> 00:55:02.880
[Amit Varma]: semantics and about just the term Hindutva and Hinduism and all of that.

00:55:02.880 --> 00:55:06.680
[Amit Varma]: And it's interesting why he objected to the term Hinduism, which he objects to, which

00:55:06.680 --> 00:55:10.920
[Amit Varma]: he says that is because, you know, an ism means a body of beliefs.

00:55:10.920 --> 00:55:13.280
[Guest]: And he wanted a word which would encompass a lot more.

00:55:13.280 --> 00:55:14.280
[Guest]: Yeah, you're right.

00:55:14.280 --> 00:55:17.840
[Guest]: He wanted a word that was bigger than sort of Hinduism.

00:55:17.840 --> 00:55:22.040
[Guest]: And he comes to the word Hindutva, which he says is a word of common usage, which I find

00:55:22.040 --> 00:55:24.160
[Guest]: hard to believe because it's not one even now.

00:55:24.160 --> 00:55:28.520
[Guest]: I mean, I don't know how many people knew the word in the 1920s.

00:55:28.520 --> 00:55:33.720
[Guest]: But he's probably the best read of the Hindutva writers.

00:55:33.720 --> 00:55:36.280
[Guest]: He's got access to a British education.

00:55:36.280 --> 00:55:38.240
[Guest]: He's multilingual properly.

00:55:38.240 --> 00:55:39.520
[Guest]: He writes a pretty good English.

00:55:39.520 --> 00:55:42.620
[Guest]: I think that he would he would stand out as a writer.

00:55:42.620 --> 00:55:50.120
[Guest]: If he wrote columns today, he has a sense of wordplay, better read and I think a better

00:55:50.120 --> 00:55:52.320
[Guest]: thinker than the people who came after him.

00:55:52.320 --> 00:55:53.320
[Amit Varma]: Right.

00:55:53.320 --> 00:55:55.720
[Amit Varma]: And there's an interesting quote from his book about the word Hindu.

00:55:55.720 --> 00:56:01.120
[Amit Varma]: I'll just read it out, quote, the reason that explains why the term Hindu cannot be synonymous

00:56:01.120 --> 00:56:06.700
[Amit Varma]: with Bharatiya or Hindi, which was used as an epithet in some senses, which synonymous

00:56:06.700 --> 00:56:11.080
[Amit Varma]: with Bharatiya or Hindi or mean an Indian only naturally introduces us to the second

00:56:11.080 --> 00:56:13.040
[Amit Varma]: essential implication of that term.

00:56:13.040 --> 00:56:17.520
[Amit Varma]: The Hindus are not merely the citizens of the Indian state because they are united not

00:56:17.520 --> 00:56:22.680
[Amit Varma]: only by the bonds of love they bear to a common motherland, but also by the bonds of a common

00:56:22.680 --> 00:56:23.680
[Amit Varma]: blood.

00:56:23.680 --> 00:56:27.240
[Amit Varma]: They are not only a nation, but also a race slash jati.

00:56:27.240 --> 00:56:32.680
[Amit Varma]: The word jati derived from the root jain to produce means a brotherhood, a race determined

00:56:32.680 --> 00:56:35.440
[Amit Varma]: by a common origin, possessing a common blood.

00:56:35.440 --> 00:56:40.580
[Amit Varma]: All Hindus claim to have in their veins the blood of the mighty race incorporated with

00:56:40.580 --> 00:56:44.920
[Amit Varma]: and descended from the Vedic fathers, the Sindhu, stop quote.

00:56:44.920 --> 00:56:50.160
[Amit Varma]: And it seemed to me in the book that while defining Hindus and Hindutva, he is relying

00:56:50.160 --> 00:56:56.040
[Amit Varma]: a lot on his sense of history, which we now know today to be completely false.

00:56:56.040 --> 00:57:02.280
[Guest]: Yeah, yeah, that's it would be hard to break it to the old man what what the recent discoveries

00:57:02.280 --> 00:57:05.920
[Guest]: in I had an episode recently with Tony Joseph and his great books.

00:57:05.920 --> 00:57:06.920
[Unknown]: Yeah, yeah, yeah.

00:57:06.920 --> 00:57:08.760
[Guest]: No, they didn't know that then.

00:57:08.760 --> 00:57:11.880
[Guest]: The other thing is that he's writing in the early 20s.

00:57:11.880 --> 00:57:17.400
[Guest]: And I think it's 1926, if I'm not mistaken, when a Mohenjo-Daro is discovered.

00:57:17.400 --> 00:57:23.300
[Guest]: So India doesn't know of the existence of Amindas Valley civilization till the mid 20s.

00:57:23.300 --> 00:57:25.280
[Guest]: And it's in this period that he's writing.

00:57:25.280 --> 00:57:30.440
[Guest]: So he's coming up with he's he's full of romance, you know, we are this great culture, but he

00:57:30.440 --> 00:57:35.680
[Guest]: probably has to wait at the traffic light while the British guy gets access first and

00:57:35.680 --> 00:57:39.360
[Guest]: you probably excluded from pubs in London.

00:57:39.360 --> 00:57:41.020
[Guest]: He was in London for a bit.

00:57:41.020 --> 00:57:46.200
[Guest]: So he that that would have had played fairly heavily on on him and he's he's writing with

00:57:46.200 --> 00:57:47.840
[Guest]: that background.

00:57:47.840 --> 00:57:53.520
[Guest]: And it should be understood that a sense of grandioseness in what he's trying to be a

00:57:53.520 --> 00:57:56.280
[Guest]: part of is inbuilt into that book.

00:57:56.280 --> 00:58:01.480
[Guest]: So yeah, it doesn't make for that good a read today.

00:58:01.480 --> 00:58:04.320
[Guest]: Unless you're looking at it purely from the academic point of view.

00:58:04.320 --> 00:58:08.000
[Guest]: It's not an easy read, because it's, it's a fairly slim work.

00:58:08.000 --> 00:58:09.000
[Guest]: It's about 50 pages.

00:58:09.000 --> 00:58:13.720
[Guest]: But you would finish it and ask what what's his point, because there's no real point at

00:58:13.720 --> 00:58:15.720
[Guest]: almost a semantic point.

00:58:15.720 --> 00:58:21.800
[Guest]: Yeah, yeah, he's one of the first guys to say that Hindus are a nation, something that

00:58:21.800 --> 00:58:25.280
[Guest]: the Muslim League would say with much more vehemence later.

00:58:25.280 --> 00:58:30.420
[Guest]: But he's clear to his mind that we are a different nation from the Muslims.

00:58:30.420 --> 00:58:35.400
[Guest]: And even within that one nation of Hindus, if you, for example, are atheist and have

00:58:35.400 --> 00:58:43.280
[Guest]: no interest at all, in anything that constitutes the Hindu faith, even then, you are a respected

00:58:43.280 --> 00:58:45.360
[Amit Varma]: member of that Hindu nation, whereas

00:58:45.360 --> 00:58:51.480
[Amit Varma]: How he sort of seems to define this sort of, you know, Hinduism as sort of a cultural construct

00:58:51.480 --> 00:58:56.160
[Amit Varma]: or whatever, and why it excludes Muslims seems to be that one thing all Hindus have in common

00:58:56.160 --> 00:59:02.680
[Amit Varma]: Hindus, quote, unquote, is that they bear allegiance to one motherland, which is, you

00:59:02.680 --> 00:59:06.840
[Amit Varma]: know, India, of course, doesn't exist, but that sort of area and his claim is that Muslims

00:59:06.840 --> 00:59:08.640
[Guest]: don't and therefore they're outside of it.

00:59:08.640 --> 00:59:09.640
[Guest]: Yeah.

00:59:09.640 --> 00:59:11.120
[Guest]: So he says that there are three tests.

00:59:11.120 --> 00:59:13.800
[Guest]: One is that you come from this part of the world.

00:59:13.800 --> 00:59:19.320
[Guest]: So Hindus do and Muslims do and Sikhs do and you know, Christians do and they all do which

00:59:19.320 --> 00:59:20.320
[Guest]: is fine.

00:59:20.320 --> 00:59:21.440
[Guest]: And he says it's fine.

00:59:21.440 --> 00:59:24.720
[Guest]: The other is bonds of blood, which he says that we all share, including those who are

00:59:24.720 --> 00:59:31.000
[Guest]: not not Hindus, because we've got we come from a parentage and a ancestry that's been

00:59:31.000 --> 00:59:32.280
[Guest]: here for a long time.

00:59:32.280 --> 00:59:33.280
[Guest]: So that's so that's fine.

00:59:33.280 --> 00:59:34.760
[Guest]: That's the that's the second one.

00:59:34.760 --> 00:59:39.720
[Guest]: The third one is the common culture bit, which you just spoke about that Hindus have a common

00:59:39.720 --> 00:59:45.960
[Guest]: culture according to him, Raksha Bandhan, Diwali.

00:59:45.960 --> 00:59:54.920
[Guest]: Such things are what constitute Hindu culture to his mind, language, food, music, these

00:59:54.920 --> 00:59:58.760
[Guest]: are not cultural aspects and he doesn't write about them.

00:59:58.760 --> 00:59:59.920
[Guest]: He has no interest in them.

00:59:59.920 --> 01:00:06.280
[Guest]: I think this is something that that carries through into Hindu thinkers, there is no interest

01:00:06.280 --> 01:00:11.320
[Guest]: at all in what Hindu high culture is or what it should be.

01:00:11.320 --> 01:00:12.840
[Guest]: They don't care whether it exists at all.

01:00:12.840 --> 01:00:14.920
[Guest]: They don't write about it in any sense.

01:00:14.920 --> 01:00:19.760
[Amit Varma]: And a lot of it is very symbiotic with the Islamic high culture and so on, you know.

01:00:19.760 --> 01:00:28.800
[Guest]: So yeah, the thing is that music, it's not that easy to be able to separate it by faith,

01:00:28.800 --> 01:00:37.320
[Guest]: you know, you've got in Europe, the high culture music, which is vocal is almost entirely in

01:00:37.320 --> 01:00:43.640
[Guest]: a language that 90% of Europe doesn't speak Italian, a lot of the music is composed by

01:00:43.640 --> 01:00:49.560
[Guest]: a group of people who are seen as mechanical and you know, the Germans, but they've got

01:00:49.560 --> 01:00:52.720
[Guest]: Mozart and they've got Beethoven and so on.

01:00:52.720 --> 01:00:57.440
[Guest]: It's not easy to say that this is this culture that we have and your culture is separate

01:00:57.440 --> 01:01:03.600
[Guest]: and then, you know, the only sort of intercourse that one culture has with another in the Savarkar

01:01:03.600 --> 01:01:05.960
[Guest]: view is through war, is through violence.

01:01:05.960 --> 01:01:09.080
[Amit Varma]: That's not the way the world works, you know.

01:01:09.080 --> 01:01:13.920
[Amit Varma]: And do you think it's not coincidental, but telling that a lot of these Hindutva ideologues

01:01:13.920 --> 01:01:19.040
[Amit Varma]: weren't actually into high culture because you imagine that people who are tuned into

01:01:19.040 --> 01:01:23.240
[Amit Varma]: culture in that sense will be less likely to have such an exclusionary view of the world.

01:01:23.240 --> 01:01:25.000
[Guest]: I hope what you're saying is right.

01:01:25.000 --> 01:01:26.000
[Guest]: It sounds nice.

01:01:26.000 --> 01:01:31.680
[Guest]: I don't know if that's the case, though, it is certainly true that you it's very difficult.

01:01:31.680 --> 01:01:38.200
[Guest]: If you've properly studied Hindustani music, to be a bigot, I'll give you an example.

01:01:38.200 --> 01:01:44.560
[Guest]: A lot of the compositions I used to have, I used to learn how to sing kirana gharana

01:01:44.560 --> 01:01:50.680
[Guest]: and about 90% of the compositions that that are sung by that gharana are the work of a

01:01:50.680 --> 01:01:56.560
[Guest]: man called Sadarang, who composed in the time of Mohammed Shah Rangeela.

01:01:56.560 --> 01:02:03.440
[Guest]: Even if you've got something like Raag Shankara, and it's an ode to Shiva, it's written by

01:02:03.440 --> 01:02:05.760
[Guest]: that man and he puts his name in it.

01:02:05.760 --> 01:02:11.280
[Guest]: So and if you hear Bhimsen Joshi sing it, there's a lovely version of his shown on Doordarshan

01:02:11.280 --> 01:02:18.040
[Guest]: that's there on YouTube, where he's singing a Shankara and the name of the author, Niyamat

01:02:18.040 --> 01:02:20.640
[Guest]: Khan Sadarang, that's his name is there in that song.

01:02:20.640 --> 01:02:25.400
[Guest]: All his songs, he would put his name in, you know, it's tough after that to be able to

01:02:25.400 --> 01:02:30.920
[Guest]: be very rigid in the way that one looks at either one's own faith or somebody else's.

01:02:30.920 --> 01:02:37.040
[Guest]: But as I said, you would find very little interest in any form of high culture of the

01:02:37.040 --> 01:02:43.640
[Guest]: Hindu, what we would look at as being Indian or Hindu high culture within the people who

01:02:43.640 --> 01:02:48.680
[Guest]: tend to push Hindutva, whether it's food, music, anything dance, it's not there.

01:02:48.680 --> 01:02:51.480
[Guest]: And what is Savarkar's approach to caste?

01:02:51.480 --> 01:02:57.160
[Guest]: One thing that becomes clear when one reads these people is all of them are Brahmin.

01:02:57.160 --> 01:03:02.720
[Guest]: So the three names that you took are all Brahmin.

01:03:02.720 --> 01:03:08.920
[Guest]: I'm not saying that there are no non-Brahmin who have contributed to this, I'm sure there

01:03:08.920 --> 01:03:09.920
[Guest]: are.

01:03:09.920 --> 01:03:12.240
[Guest]: But the corpus is primarily Brahmin.

01:03:12.240 --> 01:03:21.440
[Guest]: And so, if you look at the RSS and the people who headed it, except for one man who is a

01:03:21.440 --> 01:03:29.120
[Guest]: Thakur, who was away for a very brief period, a Sarsangachalak, all of them are a Brahmin

01:03:29.120 --> 01:03:32.800
[Guest]: and most of them are Marathi Brahmins.

01:03:32.800 --> 01:03:41.240
[Guest]: So you have that narrowness built into the thinking, which has continued and it is entirely

01:03:41.240 --> 01:03:48.800
[Guest]: absent of what we would look at as being multicultural Indian today, which we take for granted, you

01:03:48.800 --> 01:03:53.880
[Guest]: know, you would have a figure like Shah Rukh Khan or whatever, and it's not really strange.

01:03:53.880 --> 01:03:59.880
[Guest]: But it was strange, I think, to them, in the 20s, when they were thinking this up, the

01:03:59.880 --> 01:04:05.680
[Guest]: levels of sort of intercourse between them and the other was very low.

01:04:05.680 --> 01:04:10.360
[Guest]: And there are mistakes, factual errors that they make in the book, including Savarkar,

01:04:10.360 --> 01:04:16.400
[Guest]: because he doesn't really know what he's talking about when he's writing about Islam.

01:04:16.400 --> 01:04:17.400
[Amit Varma]: And what about caste?

01:04:17.400 --> 01:04:20.880
[Amit Varma]: There's an interesting quote by Savarkar, which I was unable to parse, but I'll just

01:04:20.880 --> 01:04:25.280
[Amit Varma]: read it out for you, which is, quote, all that the caste system has done is to regulate

01:04:25.280 --> 01:04:29.960
[Amit Varma]: its noble blood on lines believed and on the whole rightly believed by our saintly and

01:04:29.960 --> 01:04:35.080
[Amit Varma]: patriotic lawgivers and kings to contribute most to fertilize and enrich all that was

01:04:35.080 --> 01:04:41.560
[Amit Varma]: barren and poor, without famishing and debasing, all that was flourishing and nobly endowed,

01:04:41.560 --> 01:04:42.560
[Unknown]: stop quote.

01:04:42.560 --> 01:04:46.320
[Amit Varma]: And this is both very verbose, and he's not saying anything at all.

01:04:46.320 --> 01:04:49.040
[Guest]: That particular paragraph needs to be unpicked, I think.

01:04:49.040 --> 01:04:55.260
[Guest]: So what he's saying is, all of them support what is called varnashram, which is a division

01:04:55.260 --> 01:04:58.920
[Guest]: of society by caste, they don't have any problem with it, they think it's a good thing.

01:04:58.920 --> 01:05:04.400
[Guest]: And we can talk about Golwalkar and why he thought it was a great thing.

01:05:04.400 --> 01:05:10.760
[Guest]: But Savarkar believes that caste is beneficial.

01:05:10.760 --> 01:05:15.620
[Guest]: And he's, I think, to my mind, the first person to theorize this.

01:05:15.620 --> 01:05:20.480
[Guest]: He says that he has a problem with Buddhism.

01:05:20.480 --> 01:05:30.320
[Guest]: And he says that India became vulnerable because Buddhism took away caste from the subcontinent.

01:05:30.320 --> 01:05:35.480
[Guest]: And Afghanistan becomes Muslim, because it remains Buddhist.

01:05:35.480 --> 01:05:42.280
[Guest]: But India, because it reverts to Hinduism and caste, is able to save itself from being

01:05:42.280 --> 01:05:43.320
[Guest]: fully Muslim.

01:05:43.320 --> 01:05:48.600
[Guest]: So he thinks that caste has a positive contribution to make here.

01:05:48.600 --> 01:05:57.240
[Guest]: He and Golwalkar both thought that restricting the gene pool was a good thing.

01:05:57.240 --> 01:06:05.000
[Guest]: And that Brahmins had something special, which they could continue having, if they bred amongst

01:06:05.000 --> 01:06:06.720
[Guest]: themselves.

01:06:06.720 --> 01:06:12.160
[Guest]: And they could pass on if they were to sort of impregnate the non-Brahmin, that's what

01:06:12.160 --> 01:06:13.960
[Guest]: that long line always says.

01:06:13.960 --> 01:06:19.480
[Guest]: Savarkar also thought that, I don't know if he thought this, but he certainly wrote it,

01:06:19.480 --> 01:06:30.240
[Guest]: that caste was not fully endogamous or rigid, that it was permissible in times before ours

01:06:30.240 --> 01:06:33.400
[Guest]: for people to marry up or down.

01:06:33.400 --> 01:06:38.160
[Guest]: And he has these Sanskritic words that he uses, Anulom and so on.

01:06:38.160 --> 01:06:41.760
[Amit Varma]: In fact, he has a line here where he says, quote, a Hindu marrying a Hindu may lose his

01:06:41.760 --> 01:06:44.240
[Guest]: caste but not his Hindutva.

01:06:44.240 --> 01:06:47.160
[Guest]: So he was not a believer himself.

01:06:47.160 --> 01:06:50.960
[Guest]: So far as I know, he was not a particularly devout person.

01:06:50.960 --> 01:06:56.000
[Guest]: He was defined more by his antipathy than his faith.

01:06:56.000 --> 01:07:00.640
[Guest]: But I think he's the source of this argument that we have.

01:07:00.640 --> 01:07:05.920
[Guest]: He and maybe Vivekananda, that caste is not all bad.

01:07:05.920 --> 01:07:09.440
[Guest]: There was a period in our history when you could sort of intermarry and then that was

01:07:09.440 --> 01:07:10.440
[Guest]: fine.

01:07:10.440 --> 01:07:12.520
[Guest]: And then it's just a division of labor.

01:07:12.520 --> 01:07:14.320
[Guest]: It's not really discrimination.

01:07:14.320 --> 01:07:18.440
[Guest]: I think these are views that the middle class today would hold.

01:07:18.440 --> 01:07:23.880
[Guest]: And I think they come to us in the middle class through these two men in the main.

01:07:23.880 --> 01:07:31.200
[Guest]: Golwalkar had a very outrageous view on this.

01:07:31.200 --> 01:07:35.960
[Guest]: And it's really surprising to me that though he's referred to as being the Guruji of the

01:07:35.960 --> 01:07:41.880
[Guest]: Sangh and so on, these things haven't been made as prominent as they should have been.

01:07:41.880 --> 01:07:53.760
[Guest]: Golwalkar says that caste is good because in the ideal caste based society, access to

01:07:53.760 --> 01:07:58.400
[Guest]: money is completely separated from access to power.

01:07:58.400 --> 01:08:07.960
[Guest]: Because the Vaish deal with commerce and the Kshatriyas deal with the kingdom and authority.

01:08:07.960 --> 01:08:08.960
[Guest]: And that's great.

01:08:08.960 --> 01:08:09.960
[Amit Varma]: So you don't have a mix.

01:08:09.960 --> 01:08:12.760
[Guest]: It's like a separation of powers, a separation of power.

01:08:12.760 --> 01:08:18.920
[Guest]: And he adds that there is a selfless community on top of them that has no skin in the game,

01:08:18.920 --> 01:08:25.800
[Guest]: but is able to sort of guide and advise on how to run the whole state.

01:08:25.800 --> 01:08:28.480
[Guest]: And these are the Brahmins, obviously.

01:08:28.480 --> 01:08:32.280
[Guest]: And he says that this is what a good state should be like.

01:08:32.280 --> 01:08:37.280
[Guest]: And it's really strange to come upon him such a statement randomly in his work.

01:08:37.280 --> 01:08:46.880
[Guest]: He's written one book called A Bunch of Thoughts and it's to be as old as one is and not have

01:08:46.880 --> 01:08:54.040
[Guest]: had known that this is what the Hindutva thought is for such a long period to me is slightly

01:08:54.040 --> 01:08:55.040
[Guest]: strange.

01:08:55.040 --> 01:08:58.560
[Guest]: We don't have access in our schools to this kind of material, but we should.

01:08:58.560 --> 01:09:03.200
[Amit Varma]: And a related question I was saving for later, but we'll come back to Savarkar while I bring

01:09:03.200 --> 01:09:10.840
[Amit Varma]: it up now is that in a lot of the rhetoric of all of these guys, they actually talk about

01:09:10.840 --> 01:09:15.160
[Amit Varma]: hey, we are inclusive, we are not exclusionary, you know, for example, the RSS being called

01:09:15.160 --> 01:09:18.880
[Amit Varma]: the Rashtriya Sevak Sangh and not the Hindu Sevak Sangh, and so on.

01:09:18.880 --> 01:09:23.400
[Amit Varma]: And a lot of that rhetoric actually percolates down to the present day.

01:09:23.400 --> 01:09:27.720
[Amit Varma]: How much of that rhetoric do you think is a sort of genuine belief and how much of it

01:09:27.720 --> 01:09:28.960
[Amit Varma]: is strategic?

01:09:28.960 --> 01:09:31.960
[Guest]: I would say most of it is the latter.

01:09:31.960 --> 01:09:35.640
[Guest]: It's a strategy where you are trying to form.

01:09:35.640 --> 01:09:41.640
[Guest]: So to the RSS, the nation and the faith have never been separate.

01:09:41.640 --> 01:09:47.200
[Guest]: India is a nation and India is a nation of Hindus and Hindus are a nation.

01:09:47.200 --> 01:09:53.600
[Guest]: And so there was a debate on what to call the RSS and Gulwalkar says that at some point

01:09:53.600 --> 01:10:02.000
[Guest]: somebody suggested, you know, Hindu Swayam Sevak Sangh and Hedgewar says that no, that

01:10:02.000 --> 01:10:05.640
[Guest]: there is no difference between India and Hindu.

01:10:05.640 --> 01:10:10.160
[Guest]: And why should we call ourselves a Hindu Swayam Sevak Sangh because then we will only be one

01:10:10.160 --> 01:10:11.160
[Guest]: of many.

01:10:11.160 --> 01:10:15.520
[Guest]: We don't represent Hindu RSS, we represent India in total.

01:10:15.520 --> 01:10:18.720
[Guest]: And that is what and that I think is the strategy.

01:10:18.720 --> 01:10:22.400
[Amit Varma]: I mean, that's a sentiment you see even to the present day where if you're anti-Modi,

01:10:22.400 --> 01:10:23.400
[Amit Varma]: you're anti-national.

01:10:23.400 --> 01:10:25.280
[Guest]: Yeah, very true.

01:10:25.280 --> 01:10:31.400
[Guest]: If we've been surprised by the fact that this has become so externalized now, it's been

01:10:31.400 --> 01:10:35.720
[Guest]: there in their writing and their books for a long time.

01:10:35.720 --> 01:10:38.960
[Amit Varma]: And there's another quote of Savarkar I picked out, which reminded me so much of the present

01:10:38.960 --> 01:10:39.960
[Amit Varma]: times.

01:10:39.960 --> 01:10:44.080
[Amit Varma]: We just have to replace some words, which is, quote, in times of conflict, nations do

01:10:44.080 --> 01:10:46.000
[Amit Varma]: lose their balance of mind.

01:10:46.000 --> 01:10:50.600
[Amit Varma]: And if the Persians or others once understood by the word Hindu a thief or black man alone,

01:10:50.600 --> 01:10:55.000
[Amit Varma]: and let them remember that the word Mohammedan too, was not always mentioned to denote any

01:10:55.000 --> 01:10:59.880
[Amit Varma]: very enviable type of mankind by the Hindus either, to call a man a Musalman or better

01:10:59.880 --> 01:11:03.840
[Amit Varma]: still a Musanda was worse than calling him a brute, stop quote.

01:11:03.840 --> 01:11:08.040
[Amit Varma]: And it's very interesting that even in current times, while he's speaking of words like Hindu

01:11:08.040 --> 01:11:12.100
[Amit Varma]: and Musalman used as pejoratives, you find the same thing happening today when it comes

01:11:12.100 --> 01:11:13.100
[Amit Varma]: to liberals.

01:11:13.100 --> 01:11:17.720
[Guest]: Yeah, this what you just read out is a fairly strange part of his book, I couldn't make

01:11:17.720 --> 01:11:18.720
[Guest]: sense of it.

01:11:18.720 --> 01:11:22.200
[Guest]: But I think that in the 20s, this might have been a big thing, or at least a big thing

01:11:22.200 --> 01:11:25.120
[Guest]: in the circles that he moved around it.

01:11:25.120 --> 01:11:30.840
[Guest]: So what Savarkar is trying to do is to show that the word Hindu is in some is even if

01:11:30.840 --> 01:11:39.360
[Guest]: it is used as a word of abuse by the Muslim, and I can't think of any reason why it should

01:11:39.360 --> 01:11:40.360
[Guest]: be.

01:11:40.360 --> 01:11:43.000
[Guest]: We can give it back to you as well.

01:11:43.000 --> 01:11:44.000
[Guest]: Yeah.

01:11:44.000 --> 01:11:48.440
[Guest]: And how long that phase lasted in the part of the world that he was in where the word

01:11:48.440 --> 01:11:53.520
[Guest]: Hindu was seen as a word of abuse, I don't know, but it takes up too much space in that

01:11:53.520 --> 01:11:54.520
[Guest]: work of his.

01:11:54.520 --> 01:11:55.520
[Guest]: Yeah.

01:11:55.520 --> 01:11:56.520
[Guest]: And you're right.

01:11:56.520 --> 01:12:03.120
[Guest]: I think that the word liberal, the word secular also in in Gujarat is seen as being colored

01:12:03.120 --> 01:12:04.120
[Guest]: in a particular way.

01:12:04.120 --> 01:12:09.520
[Guest]: So the word secular means pro Muslim, and by default, it means anti Hindu.

01:12:09.520 --> 01:12:14.160
[Amit Varma]: I mean, one of the bizarre things I found was earlier the BJP would criticize the Congress

01:12:14.160 --> 01:12:18.560
[Amit Varma]: for being pseudo secular, by which would assume that if that is a criticism, then they are

01:12:18.560 --> 01:12:22.400
[Amit Varma]: criticizing the Congress for not being truly, truly secular, but being pseudo secular.

01:12:22.400 --> 01:12:27.200
[Amit Varma]: But how do you criticize people for being both pseudo secular and secular as if both

01:12:27.200 --> 01:12:29.040
[Amit Varma]: things are bad?

01:12:29.040 --> 01:12:32.880
[Guest]: Yeah, that the pseudo secular debate is gone.

01:12:32.880 --> 01:12:43.560
[Guest]: Now, the one thing to be said about Hindutva, I think that it is honest, it owns its prejudices

01:12:43.560 --> 01:12:48.600
[Guest]: and doesn't hide in the way that Congress secularism did.

01:12:48.600 --> 01:12:55.240
[Guest]: In Madhya Pradesh, in Congress run Madhya Pradesh, you could be charged under the NSA

01:12:55.240 --> 01:12:57.920
[Guest]: for the allegation of cow slaughter.

01:12:57.920 --> 01:13:05.920
[Guest]: So it's remarkable that they've just yanked the polity so quickly and so far that these

01:13:05.920 --> 01:13:09.120
[Guest]: things have become meaningless, you know, pseudo secular.

01:13:09.120 --> 01:13:15.840
[Guest]: It's, it is certainly true that in terms of terminology, the, the BJP doesn't back away

01:13:15.840 --> 01:13:20.880
[Guest]: from owning any of the things that you might accuse it of being, they will only justify

01:13:20.880 --> 01:13:21.880
[Amit Varma]: it.

01:13:21.880 --> 01:13:22.880
[Amit Varma]: Right.

01:13:22.880 --> 01:13:27.640
[Amit Varma]: And many of Savarkar's intellectual influences or political influences, rather, you know,

01:13:27.640 --> 01:13:31.480
[Amit Varma]: as various people have pointed out, came from Europe from the fascists from Mussolini and

01:13:31.480 --> 01:13:32.480
[Amit Varma]: from Hitler.

01:13:32.480 --> 01:13:37.760
[Amit Varma]: So almost as he was at pains to make the case that Hinduism was something very small and

01:13:37.760 --> 01:13:40.320
[Amit Varma]: Hindutva was broader than that.

01:13:40.320 --> 01:13:42.520
[Amit Varma]: What it seems was that it's the other way around.

01:13:42.520 --> 01:13:48.360
[Amit Varma]: Hindutva was a subset where he used ideas in Hinduism to propagate a philosophy which

01:13:48.360 --> 01:13:51.280
[Amit Varma]: wasn't really Indian to begin with, which was actually imported from there.

01:13:51.280 --> 01:13:52.660
[Guest]: No, very true, very true.

01:13:52.660 --> 01:13:58.640
[Guest]: So he's writing in the period just after the unification of Italy and he names I think

01:13:58.640 --> 01:14:04.600
[Guest]: either Mazzini or Garibaldi or maybe both in the book.

01:14:04.600 --> 01:14:14.600
[Guest]: His ideas are not those that have been sent down the ages.

01:14:14.600 --> 01:14:16.600
[Guest]: He's writing about something new.

01:14:16.600 --> 01:14:26.040
[Guest]: He's a subject in a Raj system with almost no power, sidelined and marginalized, but

01:14:26.040 --> 01:14:27.440
[Guest]: a smart man.

01:14:27.440 --> 01:14:29.600
[Guest]: And he's trying to make sense of the world.

01:14:29.600 --> 01:14:33.920
[Guest]: And he's trying to do it in a way that gives himself respect and the community and the

01:14:33.920 --> 01:14:38.160
[Guest]: people and the nation that he comes from a respect.

01:14:38.160 --> 01:14:45.040
[Guest]: But he does it in a way that sort of ultimately damages that same nation.

01:14:45.040 --> 01:14:48.960
[Amit Varma]: Moving on from Savarkar now to Golgalkar, tell me a little bit about Golgalkar.

01:14:48.960 --> 01:15:00.480
[Guest]: He's the second Sarasanga Chalak of the RSS, which is formed in 1925 by this man in Nagpur

01:15:00.480 --> 01:15:07.640
[Guest]: and who dies in 1940, and it is in the kind of mystical tradition, which the Muslims also

01:15:07.640 --> 01:15:16.040
[Guest]: have, you know, a Piro Murshid, which is what they call it, you tend to anoint your successor.

01:15:16.040 --> 01:15:25.320
[Guest]: And the story is that Golgalkar, who was fairly young, had translated a work into English.

01:15:25.320 --> 01:15:27.600
[Guest]: He was reasonably bilingual.

01:15:27.600 --> 01:15:33.000
[Guest]: I have no record or I have no access to his language in some, but it seems like he knew

01:15:33.000 --> 01:15:35.000
[Guest]: a fair bit of English.

01:15:35.000 --> 01:15:42.360
[Guest]: And he translates this work, which is titled We or Our Nationhood defined.

01:15:42.360 --> 01:15:46.680
[Guest]: And that brings him into prominence for some reason, I don't know what it is.

01:15:46.680 --> 01:15:55.480
[Guest]: And on dying, to the surprise of many, he is made the head of the RSS on the dying of

01:15:55.480 --> 01:15:56.480
[Guest]: the first head.

01:15:56.480 --> 01:15:59.000
[Guest]: He dies in 1940, and he goes through partition.

01:15:59.000 --> 01:16:06.160
[Guest]: He's a fairly young man then, he's not particularly old, he's just in his late 30s.

01:16:06.160 --> 01:16:08.160
[Guest]: And he dies in 73.

01:16:08.160 --> 01:16:14.120
[Guest]: So he's headed the RSS from a period, which was before independence, through the violence

01:16:14.120 --> 01:16:21.960
[Guest]: of partition, the constitution, through the wars with China and with Pakistan.

01:16:21.960 --> 01:16:27.040
[Guest]: And of course, the partition of Pakistan later in 71, 72, and then he dies the year after

01:16:27.040 --> 01:16:28.040
[Guest]: that.

01:16:28.040 --> 01:16:29.400
[Guest]: So he's seen a fair bit.

01:16:29.400 --> 01:16:37.720
[Guest]: He's also the man who actually makes it a national organization, he's able to reduce

01:16:37.720 --> 01:16:45.600
[Guest]: the idea of the shakha down to a simple form, very basic activity, raising the flag, wearing

01:16:45.600 --> 01:16:51.960
[Guest]: shorts if you have the shorts, coming and doing your prayers and playing kabaddi, playing

01:16:51.960 --> 01:16:56.280
[Guest]: games with sticks, and you go back after that, there's nothing else, there's no sort of intellectual

01:16:56.280 --> 01:16:58.360
[Guest]: content.

01:16:58.360 --> 01:17:02.060
[Guest]: But he's figured out that this is an easy thing to replicate.

01:17:02.060 --> 01:17:03.060
[Guest]: And it's true.

01:17:03.060 --> 01:17:07.720
[Guest]: It's the largest non-governmental organization in the world.

01:17:07.720 --> 01:17:13.000
[Guest]: It's the most powerful non-governmental organization, or at least one of them in the democratic

01:17:13.000 --> 01:17:14.000
[Guest]: world.

01:17:14.000 --> 01:17:22.200
[Guest]: I've heard that people ascribe to things like AIPAC or the NRA in the US, the RSS is much

01:17:22.200 --> 01:17:24.120
[Guest]: more powerful than any of those groups.

01:17:24.120 --> 01:17:26.440
[Guest]: I think that's his doing.

01:17:26.440 --> 01:17:36.400
[Guest]: He takes the idea of the individual Marathi Brahmin, who is willing to take up this work

01:17:36.400 --> 01:17:43.720
[Guest]: in parts of the country whose language he doesn't speak, Gujarat, sets up shop there

01:17:43.720 --> 01:17:47.680
[Guest]: in one room, doesn't marry, gives himself up to this work.

01:17:47.680 --> 01:17:48.680
[Guest]: What is this work?

01:17:48.680 --> 01:17:54.480
[Guest]: Conducting the shakha in the morning, and then for the rest of the day doing work, whatever

01:17:54.480 --> 01:17:56.260
[Guest]: it is that they wish to do.

01:17:56.260 --> 01:17:59.920
[Guest]: But making a life out of this, very few people can do this, they still do it.

01:17:59.920 --> 01:18:08.280
[Guest]: You have people from the RSS that run single teacher schools across the Adivasi belt, but

01:18:08.280 --> 01:18:14.320
[Guest]: they're bringing people out of what they think as being a manimism and into a more puranic

01:18:14.320 --> 01:18:15.880
[Guest]: faith.

01:18:15.880 --> 01:18:21.540
[Guest]: So he formulates this sort of easily replicable model, and he does it.

01:18:21.540 --> 01:18:27.120
[Guest]: So very soon you've got hundreds of these shakhas opening all over the country.

01:18:27.120 --> 01:18:30.600
[Guest]: Ten years after he takes over the RSS, we have a constitution.

01:18:30.600 --> 01:18:35.060
[Guest]: Two years after that, we have the first election, and the Jana Sangh is formed.

01:18:35.060 --> 01:18:41.800
[Guest]: So then he supplies material to the party in terms of cadre, in terms of people who

01:18:41.800 --> 01:18:49.840
[Guest]: can stand, Vajpayee is one, Madhwani is another, who come out of that, Shekhawat is a third.

01:18:49.840 --> 01:18:58.280
[Guest]: And he's there behind all of this, running the shakhas, making sure that the organization

01:18:58.280 --> 01:19:03.680
[Guest]: is continuously built and built to the end that he thought it was right.

01:19:03.680 --> 01:19:08.520
[Guest]: I think the shakha should be seen in a particular light.

01:19:08.520 --> 01:19:15.480
[Guest]: Why do they do exercises that require training with lathis, who are they training to fight

01:19:15.480 --> 01:19:16.480
[Guest]: against?

01:19:16.480 --> 01:19:20.640
[Guest]: Are they going to fight the Chinese at the border?

01:19:20.640 --> 01:19:21.640
[Guest]: No, that's not.

01:19:21.640 --> 01:19:23.920
[Guest]: They're going to fight other Indians.

01:19:23.920 --> 01:19:25.200
[Guest]: That's what the shakha does.

01:19:25.200 --> 01:19:30.640
[Guest]: In a riot, the shakha is the locus of the violence.

01:19:30.640 --> 01:19:35.400
[Guest]: It's the one place where the neighborhood young men who've trained in the physical stuff

01:19:35.400 --> 01:19:41.280
[Guest]: who know one another and can bond and can trust one another, can take a collective action

01:19:41.280 --> 01:19:46.080
[Guest]: that the individual so called cowardly Hindu doesn't.

01:19:46.080 --> 01:19:49.840
[Guest]: And he does a very good job of it.

01:19:49.840 --> 01:19:56.320
[Guest]: The RSS can overwhelm the security apparatus of the average Indian city very easily, as

01:19:56.320 --> 01:19:58.320
[Amit Varma]: we've seen in Gujarat.

01:19:58.320 --> 01:20:03.840
[Amit Varma]: So all the memes that are floating around after Pulwama that you know, the RSS should

01:20:03.840 --> 01:20:07.120
[Amit Varma]: send people with their sticks to fight at the border actually misplaced because the

01:20:07.120 --> 01:20:09.560
[Guest]: idea is not that they're going to fight Pakistan and China.

01:20:09.560 --> 01:20:14.880
[Guest]: Yeah, well, to them, I think Pakistan is just an extension of the Indian Muslim.

01:20:14.880 --> 01:20:19.560
[Guest]: I don't think they see it in a way that most other Indians would, you would see it as a

01:20:19.560 --> 01:20:20.560
[Guest]: foreign country.

01:20:20.560 --> 01:20:24.480
[Guest]: You wouldn't I mean, you would you would send some sort of brotherhood in terms of the food

01:20:24.480 --> 01:20:27.640
[Guest]: being the same and the music being the same and you know.

01:20:27.640 --> 01:20:33.040
[Guest]: But it's it's as different to somebody from Gujarat as Tamil Nadu would be or whatever.

01:20:33.040 --> 01:20:34.440
[Guest]: It's a different place.

01:20:34.440 --> 01:20:36.320
[Guest]: And it is separated also by government.

01:20:36.320 --> 01:20:38.200
[Guest]: So it would be properly foreign for them.

01:20:38.200 --> 01:20:39.200
[Guest]: It's not that way.

01:20:39.200 --> 01:20:44.000
[Guest]: I think they would see the Muslim in Gulbarga as being identical to the one in Lahore.

01:20:44.000 --> 01:20:45.120
[Guest]: It's the same thing.

01:20:45.120 --> 01:20:46.120
[Guest]: It's yours.

01:20:46.120 --> 01:20:49.600
[Guest]: You're on my land and you don't belong in my country.

01:20:49.600 --> 01:20:51.760
[Guest]: If you do belong, it is on the sufferance.

01:20:51.760 --> 01:20:55.320
[Guest]: I think that is that that they would say that that okay, it's fine.

01:20:55.320 --> 01:21:02.520
[Guest]: But we whoever we is has a privilege and rights that you don't.

01:21:02.520 --> 01:21:07.400
[Amit Varma]: And the way you describe it, it sounds almost that Golwalkar was a management and strategic

01:21:07.400 --> 01:21:11.800
[Amit Varma]: genius of sorts that he figured out that this was a way to grow the organization, build

01:21:11.800 --> 01:21:15.000
[Amit Varma]: feeling of community and brotherhood and all of those things.

01:21:15.000 --> 01:21:19.080
[Amit Varma]: But did these things just happen or did he actually plan them that way?

01:21:19.080 --> 01:21:24.200
[Guest]: I'm not sure what the pre-Golwalkar RSS looked like.

01:21:24.200 --> 01:21:34.040
[Guest]: Mr. Modi in his very fawning a biographical sketch of Golwalkar recounts this sort of

01:21:34.040 --> 01:21:37.840
[Guest]: an interview that Golwalkar has with somebody and that and the person says, why are you

01:21:37.840 --> 01:21:43.520
[Guest]: just calling people over and doing this, you know, simple childish stuff like playing games

01:21:43.520 --> 01:21:44.520
[Guest]: and all.

01:21:44.520 --> 01:21:51.200
[Guest]: And Golwalkar says to him that we are masters of the science of organization.

01:21:51.200 --> 01:21:56.400
[Guest]: He uses the words in English according to Mr. Modi.

01:21:56.400 --> 01:22:01.280
[Guest]: And I think that certainly Mr. Modi sees him in that light that he's somebody who was able

01:22:01.280 --> 01:22:10.600
[Guest]: to create a format that especially in urban India was easy to replicate and which he did

01:22:10.600 --> 01:22:11.600
[Guest]: replicate.

01:22:11.600 --> 01:22:19.080
[Guest]: To be fair, most of the expansion of the RSS from being hundreds across India to being

01:22:19.080 --> 01:22:22.280
[Guest]: the tens of thousands happened much after his death.

01:22:22.280 --> 01:22:24.360
[Amit Varma]: It happened in the 80s and 90s.

01:22:24.360 --> 01:22:29.120
[Amit Varma]: And despite all this, like you said that there wasn't much intellectual content coming from

01:22:29.120 --> 01:22:33.600
[Amit Varma]: Golwalkar, like in your notes, there's a line I'll quote on Golwalkar, which you say where

01:22:33.600 --> 01:22:38.400
[Amit Varma]: you say, quote, he sets great store by feeling and emotion because thinking takes away from

01:22:38.400 --> 01:22:41.500
[Amit Varma]: the strong sense of identity and communitarianism.

01:22:41.500 --> 01:22:42.500
[Amit Varma]: That is his passion.

01:22:42.500 --> 01:22:43.500
[Guest]: Stop quote.

01:22:43.500 --> 01:22:50.000
[Guest]: So there is no, so if you think of an ideology, it would be a set of rules or principles that

01:22:50.000 --> 01:22:54.400
[Guest]: have something basic that is underlying that you're trying to reach at something that is

01:22:54.400 --> 01:22:55.400
[Guest]: large.

01:22:55.400 --> 01:22:59.960
[Guest]: There's nothing like that in the writing, certainly of Golwalkar.

01:22:59.960 --> 01:23:05.680
[Guest]: And in none of the Hindutva, Amadei logs, will you find anything that even approaches

01:23:05.680 --> 01:23:07.320
[Guest]: an ideology?

01:23:07.320 --> 01:23:08.320
[Guest]: It's quite basic.

01:23:08.320 --> 01:23:19.160
[Guest]: They will talk very lightly of Greek thought or so Upadhyay says that there are that modern

01:23:19.160 --> 01:23:20.480
[Guest]: Western systems.

01:23:20.480 --> 01:23:29.200
[Guest]: And he says that the three main ones are nationalism, democracy, and socialism are in some way not

01:23:29.200 --> 01:23:35.280
[Guest]: whole and people in the West feel insecure because of this lack of sort of wholesomeness.

01:23:35.280 --> 01:23:39.780
[Guest]: And he says, the reason is that they are not able to satisfy the four aspects of human

01:23:39.780 --> 01:23:40.780
[Guest]: being.

01:23:40.780 --> 01:23:48.920
[Guest]: And he says that these four aspects are body, mind, intellect, and soul, how mind is different

01:23:48.920 --> 01:23:49.960
[Guest]: from the intellect.

01:23:49.960 --> 01:23:52.120
[Guest]: He doesn't explain and what soul is.

01:23:52.120 --> 01:23:59.340
[Guest]: He doesn't say Golwalkar talks about the fact that, okay, we are quite bad at science, fine.

01:23:59.340 --> 01:24:02.880
[Guest]: But Hindus are masters of the science of spirit.

01:24:02.880 --> 01:24:03.880
[Guest]: What does that mean?

01:24:03.880 --> 01:24:04.880
[Guest]: What does spirit mean?

01:24:04.880 --> 01:24:11.160
[Guest]: Does he mean it in the sense of sort of he and both, Upadhyay, do they both mean it in

01:24:11.160 --> 01:24:14.920
[Guest]: the sense of the transmigration of souls and things like that?

01:24:14.920 --> 01:24:18.000
[Guest]: You don't know because they don't really expand.

01:24:18.000 --> 01:24:22.200
[Guest]: They just assume that the reader will nod his head and say, oh, yeah, you know, there

01:24:22.200 --> 01:24:25.920
[Guest]: are four parts to the human being, body, mind, intellect, and soul.

01:24:25.920 --> 01:24:29.720
[Guest]: And that Hindus are the masters of the science of spirit.

01:24:29.720 --> 01:24:32.560
[Guest]: And what is the justification that Golwalkar gives for this?

01:24:32.560 --> 01:24:36.880
[Guest]: He says that, well, Jesus only saw Satan.

01:24:36.880 --> 01:24:40.600
[Guest]: And you know, Mohammed only met Gabriel.

01:24:40.600 --> 01:24:47.320
[Guest]: It is the Hindu saints that actually saw God and witnessed God and knew about his attributes.

01:24:47.320 --> 01:24:53.940
[Guest]: But from there to have a like, like an objective discussion is not easy, because you're talking

01:24:53.940 --> 01:24:58.040
[Guest]: to somebody who believes in that sort of thing.

01:24:58.040 --> 01:25:01.160
[Guest]: So it's quite vacuous in many ways.

01:25:01.160 --> 01:25:06.680
[Guest]: You know, it's quite disappointing, because if you see some of the more militaristic stuff

01:25:06.680 --> 01:25:13.560
[Guest]: that that the other faiths have done, there is a fair amount of intellectual rigor there.

01:25:13.560 --> 01:25:14.560
[Guest]: There is none here.

01:25:14.560 --> 01:25:19.520
[Amit Varma]: There is it's nothing that there's a lot of what seems to be the waffling you find in

01:25:19.520 --> 01:25:21.360
[Amit Varma]: self-help books.

01:25:21.360 --> 01:25:28.160
[Amit Varma]: And also a lot of sort of the way he, Golwalkar seems to rouse his followers is not by talking

01:25:28.160 --> 01:25:32.520
[Amit Varma]: about Hindutva itself, but by the threats that it faces from outside, for example.

01:25:32.520 --> 01:25:34.320
[Guest]: Yeah, tell me a bit about that.

01:25:34.320 --> 01:25:36.040
[Guest]: Well, threat mostly inside.

01:25:36.040 --> 01:25:41.760
[Guest]: So the fact is that, that the enemy is already within us and needs to be sorted.

01:25:41.760 --> 01:25:48.320
[Guest]: So I think that is the one thing that is constant to all of these people who wrote about the

01:25:48.320 --> 01:25:54.680
[Guest]: subject, that the enemy is primarily the Indian Muslim who needs to be fixed, needs to be

01:25:54.680 --> 01:25:55.680
[Guest]: put in their place.

01:25:55.680 --> 01:25:59.080
[Guest]: But there's too many of them, we don't know what to do with them.

01:25:59.080 --> 01:26:06.640
[Guest]: But we will show that we are not going to be the kind of nation we were 1000 years ago,

01:26:06.640 --> 01:26:11.120
[Guest]: that we were the embodiment of the ideal spirit, you know, caste was very good.

01:26:11.120 --> 01:26:15.280
[Guest]: And we had these great kings, then these people came and they conquered us.

01:26:15.280 --> 01:26:23.680
[Guest]: The idea of slavery and being subjects over 1000 years runs very strongly through this.

01:26:23.680 --> 01:26:30.280
[Guest]: There is a strong sense of belief that in some way what Modi represents today is the

01:26:30.280 --> 01:26:39.360
[Guest]: breaking out from that slavery, both the period of direct rule by foreigners, and by those

01:26:39.360 --> 01:26:40.840
[Amit Varma]: that they left behind.

01:26:40.840 --> 01:26:42.720
[Amit Varma]: And this is again a question I was saving for the end.

01:26:42.720 --> 01:26:45.560
[Amit Varma]: But since it's come up now, I'll ask it anyway.

01:26:45.560 --> 01:26:50.820
[Amit Varma]: And something I wonder about, which is that there is a sense of grievance and the humiliation

01:26:50.820 --> 01:26:52.760
[Amit Varma]: of the past and so on and so forth.

01:26:52.760 --> 01:26:56.520
[Amit Varma]: And some of it isn't even true, it's just made up.

01:26:56.520 --> 01:27:00.800
[Amit Varma]: But the point is that this is the sort of history that these guys invoke to rouse people

01:27:00.800 --> 01:27:02.220
[Amit Varma]: to passion.

01:27:02.220 --> 01:27:09.080
[Amit Varma]: But the common person like growing up in the India that you are, where Hindus are the majority

01:27:09.080 --> 01:27:15.800
[Amit Varma]: and Brahmins especially are incredibly privileged, where do they get this historic sense of humiliation

01:27:15.800 --> 01:27:16.800
[Amit Varma]: from?

01:27:16.800 --> 01:27:20.280
[Amit Varma]: It's not that they live amid history and amid the ruins or anything like that.

01:27:20.280 --> 01:27:25.120
[Amit Varma]: You know, why does it rouse them to such passion that a temple was broken so many years ago,

01:27:25.120 --> 01:27:29.880
[Amit Varma]: or, you know, the Muslims ruled us in centuries of which there is really no sign today.

01:27:29.880 --> 01:27:34.520
[Guest]: Some would say that this is the narrative that the British constructed and left behind,

01:27:34.520 --> 01:27:42.200
[Guest]: that the first schools in Gujarat only come in the 1850s.

01:27:42.200 --> 01:27:46.840
[Guest]: So Elphinstone builds them, which is only 170 years ago, right?

01:27:46.840 --> 01:27:51.160
[Guest]: So before that, you don't have any form of organized teaching.

01:27:51.160 --> 01:27:57.080
[Guest]: So when do you come into group think, when do you have a sense of your nationhood?

01:27:57.080 --> 01:28:06.560
[Guest]: Fairly recently, as a Gujarati, I'd say that my own sense of bigotry and prejudice comes

01:28:06.560 --> 01:28:14.880
[Guest]: out of a popular history of four volumes written by K M Munshi on Somnath.

01:28:14.880 --> 01:28:22.920
[Guest]: And even though you might not know much about histories, particularly in the sense of dates

01:28:22.920 --> 01:28:29.840
[Guest]: and such things, you will have had a sense of Somnath in Gujarat, purely through these

01:28:29.840 --> 01:28:34.080
[Guest]: four fairly recent novels.

01:28:34.080 --> 01:28:40.960
[Guest]: And I think that a lot of it might be that, that it's a, the fact that it's a fairly recently

01:28:40.960 --> 01:28:46.560
[Guest]: educated nation, at the turn of the 20th century, 4% of India was illiterate.

01:28:46.560 --> 01:28:55.120
[Guest]: I mean, it's quite remarkable to think of that, it's not that long ago, just 119 years.

01:28:55.120 --> 01:29:01.360
[Guest]: And secondly, that you're living cheek by jowl with a very large community, which doesn't

01:29:01.360 --> 01:29:11.160
[Guest]: share what you think are the pillars of your own faith, you know, vegetarianism or whatever

01:29:11.160 --> 01:29:12.160
[Guest]: else.

01:29:12.160 --> 01:29:15.240
[Guest]: So yeah, it's, but I don't know for sure.

01:29:15.240 --> 01:29:16.240
[Guest]: I haven't thought about that.

01:29:16.240 --> 01:29:20.000
[Guest]: This is the first time that I'm actually confronted, why do they feel this?

01:29:20.000 --> 01:29:21.200
[Guest]: I really don't know.

01:29:21.200 --> 01:29:25.400
[Amit Varma]: Because it also strikes me that, you know, a lot of people who are born Hindu, aren't

01:29:25.400 --> 01:29:28.920
[Amit Varma]: reading these books, for example, the ones you pointed out about Somnath, they're not

01:29:28.920 --> 01:29:31.920
[Amit Varma]: surrounded by signs of that humiliation.

01:29:31.920 --> 01:29:37.440
[Amit Varma]: So part of the reason that these histories persist, or these grievances persist, must

01:29:37.440 --> 01:29:43.160
[Amit Varma]: be not only because they're being brainwashed into it, but because they need these to validate

01:29:43.160 --> 01:29:44.160
[Amit Varma]: something else.

01:29:44.160 --> 01:29:48.200
[Amit Varma]: Maybe there's an innate bigotry and they need to build this backstory to validate that.

01:29:48.200 --> 01:29:49.320
[Amit Varma]: Is that possible?

01:29:49.320 --> 01:29:57.920
[Guest]: I know for sure that the resistance of the Indian Muslim to the monopolization of power

01:29:57.920 --> 01:30:05.480
[Guest]: by the Hindus under Congress is not seen sympathetically at all by most Hindus.

01:30:05.480 --> 01:30:13.680
[Guest]: So for us, when we are taught in school, Jinnah is the villain.

01:30:13.680 --> 01:30:20.100
[Guest]: And if you're sort of Hindutva minded, then the Congress got conned, or they were part

01:30:20.100 --> 01:30:21.580
[Guest]: of the game itself.

01:30:21.580 --> 01:30:28.520
[Guest]: But the idea that there was a legitimate claim to a share in power is not seen sympathetically.

01:30:28.520 --> 01:30:37.560
[Guest]: Today you could give data to the average Indian middle class person and say that the last

01:30:37.560 --> 01:30:46.840
[Guest]: person from Gujarat, who is Muslim, who was elected to the Lok Sabha came in 1985.

01:30:46.840 --> 01:30:51.080
[Guest]: And this is a community that has produced Premji, that has produced Khura Kiwala, that

01:30:51.080 --> 01:31:00.720
[Guest]: has produced Jinnah, Ahmed Patel, last one in 85, not a single person from UP today has

01:31:00.720 --> 01:31:04.680
[Guest]: no Muslim in the Lok Sabha.

01:31:04.680 --> 01:31:14.000
[Guest]: The BJP of the 1100 or 1200 legislators they have nationally have four Muslims.

01:31:14.000 --> 01:31:16.320
[Guest]: Does this make people uncomfortable?

01:31:16.320 --> 01:31:19.640
[Guest]: I would say no, they're okay with it.

01:31:19.640 --> 01:31:30.600
[Guest]: But in such a society, it's easy to see why you can demonize a community and feel no sympathy

01:31:30.600 --> 01:31:35.560
[Guest]: for it and have no empathy for the fact that you've marginalized them totally from power

01:31:35.560 --> 01:31:40.440
[Guest]: and any demand that they might make to share power would be seen in negative terms, you

01:31:40.440 --> 01:31:44.560
[Guest]: know, that you're trying to break up my country or like whatever else.

01:31:44.560 --> 01:31:50.080
[Guest]: So I don't know what the wellspring is, where it comes from for people in the 20s.

01:31:50.080 --> 01:31:57.000
[Guest]: But certainly, after 47 partition would be one great trigger for this hatred.

01:31:57.000 --> 01:32:02.880
[Amit Varma]: And you know, a tangential question here, which is that, if we look at all the other

01:32:02.880 --> 01:32:07.160
[Amit Varma]: parties like the Congress and so on, it's easy to say that they are basically election

01:32:07.160 --> 01:32:10.560
[Amit Varma]: winning machines, and there's no core philosophy to them.

01:32:10.560 --> 01:32:15.360
[Amit Varma]: And at least when it comes to the BJP, there is some kind of however badly formulated this,

01:32:15.360 --> 01:32:22.000
[Amit Varma]: there are some core philosophical beliefs, but where that seems to come under challenge

01:32:22.000 --> 01:32:27.160
[Amit Varma]: is when you look at how they won 2014, for example, someone I had on my show a few months

01:32:27.160 --> 01:32:30.440
[Amit Varma]: ago was Prashanth Jha, who wrote the book about how the BJP won.

01:32:30.440 --> 01:32:35.160
[Amit Varma]: And he points out about how Amit Shah went along building those sort of caste coalitions.

01:32:35.160 --> 01:32:38.400
[Amit Varma]: And so very early on in UP, for example, they figured out, okay, we are not getting the

01:32:38.400 --> 01:32:39.400
[Amit Varma]: Muslim vote.

01:32:39.400 --> 01:32:41.600
[Amit Varma]: Obviously, they will nominate someone there.

01:32:41.600 --> 01:32:47.400
[Amit Varma]: But then among the OBCs, they know that there are resentments among the non-Yadav OBCs.

01:32:47.400 --> 01:32:51.120
[Amit Varma]: So they bring them in among the non-Jatav Dalits against Mayawati.

01:32:51.120 --> 01:32:54.680
[Amit Varma]: So they try to bring them into the fold and he tries to bring a coalition like that.

01:32:54.680 --> 01:32:59.440
[Amit Varma]: And at a certain point, Jha in his book quotes a Dalit scholar as saying that BJP in some

01:32:59.440 --> 01:33:03.960
[Amit Varma]: places is actually the Dalit party, because they're not only getting Dalit office bearers,

01:33:03.960 --> 01:33:09.740
[Amit Varma]: but they're building Dalit temples, and so on and actually investing in the community.

01:33:09.740 --> 01:33:13.600
[Amit Varma]: And my question here is not of how genuine that is, or whatever is obviously driven by

01:33:13.600 --> 01:33:15.320
[Amit Varma]: political imperatives.

01:33:15.320 --> 01:33:20.040
[Amit Varma]: But then with the BJP, there is, again, and I'm just thinking aloud, that there is then

01:33:20.040 --> 01:33:24.440
[Amit Varma]: that dissonance between what seems to be a guiding philosophy, which is not an inclusive

01:33:24.440 --> 01:33:29.880
[Amit Varma]: guiding philosophy, on one hand, and on the other hand, the imperatives of winning elections,

01:33:29.880 --> 01:33:34.160
[Amit Varma]: which typically would make parties sociopathic in the sense that they don't really then have

01:33:34.160 --> 01:33:37.240
[Amit Varma]: any core beliefs, they just do whatever it takes to win votes.

01:33:37.240 --> 01:33:43.480
[Guest]: The sort of really interesting thing about the BJP's attitude to caste is that it has

01:33:43.480 --> 01:33:52.400
[Guest]: not allowed to any large extent, what its ideologues have written into practice.

01:33:52.400 --> 01:33:56.400
[Guest]: As long as you are vaguely okay with the fact that they felt that caste was a good thing

01:33:56.400 --> 01:34:02.320
[Guest]: and so on, it doesn't really matter that you are not yourself a Brahmin.

01:34:02.320 --> 01:34:05.560
[Guest]: You can become the leader of India, if you're not a Brahmin.

01:34:05.560 --> 01:34:06.560
[Guest]: But you have to be Brahminical.

01:34:06.560 --> 01:34:09.320
[Guest]: I think that's what the rules say.

01:34:09.320 --> 01:34:12.520
[Guest]: So Mr. Modi comes from a community that is meat eating.

01:34:12.520 --> 01:34:15.920
[Amit Varma]: But then Sabarkar and Golvarkar would use that to say, let's see inclusive, we mean

01:34:15.920 --> 01:34:18.720
[Amit Varma]: Hinduism is a way of life and not as...

01:34:18.720 --> 01:34:19.720
[Guest]: Indeed.

01:34:19.720 --> 01:34:20.720
[Guest]: Yeah.

01:34:20.720 --> 01:34:21.720
[Guest]: They have that space.

01:34:21.720 --> 01:34:32.680
[Guest]: They also have, there is a brotherhood, there is a sense that when two swayamsevaks meet,

01:34:32.680 --> 01:34:38.080
[Guest]: there is a shared idea of this country, there is a shared idea of who the enemy is, there's

01:34:38.080 --> 01:34:42.360
[Guest]: a shared idea of what the problems are.

01:34:42.360 --> 01:34:47.680
[Guest]: And I think that has held them together and given them a kind of network, which no other

01:34:47.680 --> 01:34:55.560
[Guest]: party has, and no other party can have, outside of the jati, abiradhari networks, that most

01:34:55.560 --> 01:35:01.680
[Guest]: parties run on in the north, for example, the BJP has a kind of underlying layer, especially

01:35:01.680 --> 01:35:06.960
[Guest]: in towns and cities, which holds the whole project together.

01:35:06.960 --> 01:35:11.240
[Amit Varma]: Going back to Golvarkar now, you know, as you pointed out a few years after he becomes

01:35:11.240 --> 01:35:14.000
[Amit Varma]: the head of the RSS, you have partition and all of that.

01:35:14.000 --> 01:35:19.360
[Amit Varma]: And I noticed one interesting fact about Golvarkar was that he used to make Sanskrit the national

01:35:19.360 --> 01:35:24.080
[Amit Varma]: language, much as, you know, Urdu became the national language there.

01:35:24.080 --> 01:35:31.120
[Amit Varma]: To what extent is the Pakistan project actually a model or an inspiration for the Hindutva

01:35:31.120 --> 01:35:35.840
[Amit Varma]: leading thinkers to do a Hindu version of that?

01:35:35.840 --> 01:35:38.600
[Guest]: I don't know.

01:35:38.600 --> 01:35:44.440
[Guest]: Pakistan's origins are from the modernist point of view, they are not of anti-deluvian.

01:35:44.440 --> 01:35:50.000
[Guest]: So the person who coined the word Pakistan was in London, Allama Iqbal, who thought of

01:35:50.000 --> 01:35:57.680
[Guest]: this kind of utopia in Northwest India, where people would reformulate Islam and make it

01:35:57.680 --> 01:36:03.760
[Guest]: modern was not a traditionalist at all.

01:36:03.760 --> 01:36:06.280
[Guest]: So you would think of them as being extreme.

01:36:06.280 --> 01:36:08.760
[Guest]: They were very, very advanced in the way that they were thinking.

01:36:08.760 --> 01:36:11.760
[Guest]: That's not the Hindutva project.

01:36:11.760 --> 01:36:18.120
[Guest]: The Hindutva project is most comfortable looking back rather than looking in front, that the

01:36:18.120 --> 01:36:23.920
[Guest]: stronger emotions are about the defeats of the past and so on.

01:36:23.920 --> 01:36:27.200
[Guest]: So I don't know whether it was a model.

01:36:27.200 --> 01:36:32.160
[Guest]: I do know that he wanted Sanskrit in some sense to be elevated, but he also felt that

01:36:32.160 --> 01:36:35.760
[Guest]: till such time as everybody learned it, it was okay to use Hindi.

01:36:35.760 --> 01:36:41.120
[Guest]: And of course, it ran into trouble because of the revolution in the South and the rebellion,

01:36:41.120 --> 01:36:49.840
[Guest]: I should say, and then he would have, you know, withdrawn that the vehemence.

01:36:49.840 --> 01:36:53.880
[Guest]: But for most of the 60s and 70s, the RSS had very little power.

01:36:53.880 --> 01:36:59.600
[Guest]: The Janasang, the previous version of the BJP had about two and a half percent of the

01:36:59.600 --> 01:37:03.760
[Guest]: vote in Gujarat for most of the 70s.

01:37:03.760 --> 01:37:08.400
[Guest]: Till Babri happens, they are a very marginal power.

01:37:08.400 --> 01:37:14.280
[Guest]: So even though they might have felt it strongly, and even if they might have externalized things

01:37:14.280 --> 01:37:18.040
[Guest]: like we should make Sanskrit the language of the country, they had very little power

01:37:18.040 --> 01:37:25.000
[Guest]: or means to be able to either amplify their view or certainly to be able to impose it.

01:37:25.000 --> 01:37:29.200
[Amit Varma]: So was Babri something that was inevitable as a trigger of a change that was coming or

01:37:29.200 --> 01:37:33.840
[Amit Varma]: was it an episode that just happened to make this whole thing explode and it won't have

01:37:33.840 --> 01:37:34.840
[Guest]: otherwise?

01:37:34.840 --> 01:37:39.960
[Guest]: I would recommend a book written by two men called both called Jha, I think, to your listeners

01:37:39.960 --> 01:37:42.560
[Guest]: on the Babri issue.

01:37:42.560 --> 01:37:43.560
[Guest]: It was festering.

01:37:43.560 --> 01:37:50.200
[Guest]: So it's history predates of independence, the controversy, and then it's given fresh

01:37:50.200 --> 01:37:52.400
[Guest]: life in the 80s.

01:37:52.400 --> 01:38:00.440
[Guest]: But I believe that Hindutva would have found its sureness of foot elsewhere if it had not

01:38:00.440 --> 01:38:01.440
[Guest]: been for Babri.

01:38:01.440 --> 01:38:07.880
[Guest]: Babri was very important, it gave them a momentum as a political party, which they would never

01:38:07.880 --> 01:38:11.080
[Guest]: have been able to find, you know, otherwise.

01:38:11.080 --> 01:38:16.240
[Guest]: But we should also remember that the momentum and the expansion of the party happens primarily

01:38:16.240 --> 01:38:22.560
[Guest]: also through civic violence, when the BJP participates in some way in the murder of

01:38:22.560 --> 01:38:28.160
[Guest]: the Muslims of this country, it is able to expand itself.

01:38:28.160 --> 01:38:38.240
[Guest]: In the recent phase, the full blown, you know, riot has been replaced with a series of sort

01:38:38.240 --> 01:38:48.040
[Guest]: of episodes, lynchings or, you know, things like what happened in UP.

01:38:48.040 --> 01:38:53.400
[Guest]: But it is not just the symbolic aspect of the movement, I think the campaign is also

01:38:53.400 --> 01:39:00.360
[Guest]: built on mobilizing people, validating the violence that they perpetrate, and they have

01:39:00.360 --> 01:39:03.360
[Guest]: no shame in being able to accept that fact.

01:39:03.360 --> 01:39:05.040
[Amit Varma]: I've taken up a lot of your time.

01:39:05.040 --> 01:39:09.160
[Amit Varma]: So I think we'll skip talking about Upadhyaya and I'll just recommend my listeners to read

01:39:09.160 --> 01:39:10.960
[Amit Varma]: your book when it comes out.

01:39:10.960 --> 01:39:13.000
[Amit Varma]: But some few, a few broader questions.

01:39:13.000 --> 01:39:16.840
[Amit Varma]: Now the term Hindu Rashtra, obviously, as you pointed out, was coined by Hegdevar, like

01:39:16.840 --> 01:39:22.400
[Amit Varma]: he met Savarkar in 25 and later Dattier formed the RSS and instead of Hindutva, he used the

01:39:22.400 --> 01:39:26.320
[Amit Varma]: term Hindu Rashtra, I mean, whether he coined it or not.

01:39:26.320 --> 01:39:30.240
[Amit Varma]: Now, we are talking about the Hindu Rashtra today and you're writing this book because

01:39:30.240 --> 01:39:36.160
[Amit Varma]: of political events, what has happened since 2014, and the new dominance of the BJP sort

01:39:36.160 --> 01:39:38.760
[Amit Varma]: of as a central pole of Indian politics.

01:39:38.760 --> 01:39:44.260
[Amit Varma]: But my question is, does the Hindu Rashtra exist outside of politics?

01:39:44.260 --> 01:39:46.040
[Amit Varma]: Is it primarily a culture thing?

01:39:46.040 --> 01:39:50.560
[Amit Varma]: And is the politics just one inevitable outcome of that?

01:39:50.560 --> 01:39:53.400
[Guest]: I think politics amplifies it a lot.

01:39:53.400 --> 01:39:55.920
[Guest]: It does exist outside of politics.

01:39:55.920 --> 01:39:59.260
[Guest]: Maybe it's not as pronounced as it is.

01:39:59.260 --> 01:40:06.920
[Guest]: Maybe if it were not molested by politics, it would remain dormant.

01:40:06.920 --> 01:40:08.040
[Guest]: It does exist.

01:40:08.040 --> 01:40:09.040
[Guest]: It is there.

01:40:09.040 --> 01:40:14.120
[Guest]: I think that the idea, if it were not, it would not be the case that we are the only

01:40:14.120 --> 01:40:20.040
[Guest]: country in South Asia that is not majoritarian by law, or has tried to be at some point.

01:40:20.040 --> 01:40:24.640
[Guest]: It is, there is something about this part of the world, where if you, where might is

01:40:24.640 --> 01:40:28.760
[Guest]: right, if there's more of you than the other or the people that you think of as being the

01:40:28.760 --> 01:40:29.760
[Amit Varma]: other.

01:40:29.760 --> 01:40:32.680
[Amit Varma]: But also the fact that we didn't give into majoritarianism could be a combination of

01:40:32.680 --> 01:40:37.560
[Amit Varma]: circumstance that we had the people we had framing the constitution and inertia.

01:40:37.560 --> 01:40:38.560
[Guest]: Maybe.

01:40:38.560 --> 01:40:42.040
[Guest]: Yeah, that's a good, that's a good explanation.

01:40:42.040 --> 01:40:46.880
[Guest]: But I think that we would struggle even more than the Muslims of Pakistan in trying to

01:40:46.880 --> 01:40:54.360
[Guest]: find what that right, a projection of faith onto law is.

01:40:54.360 --> 01:40:55.360
[Guest]: It would be very difficult.

01:40:55.360 --> 01:40:57.000
[Amit Varma]: So I'll ask you to expand on that now.

01:40:57.000 --> 01:41:00.920
[Amit Varma]: You said at the start of the episode that there can be no such thing as a Hindutva constitution.

01:41:00.920 --> 01:41:12.720
[Guest]: You know, after Ram comes back from Ayodhya, there is a turmoil in the court.

01:41:12.720 --> 01:41:17.120
[Guest]: And there is a Brahmin who comes to him with his son who's dead.

01:41:17.120 --> 01:41:22.560
[Guest]: And it turns and this, this son is a flawless, he's not done a thing wrong in his life.

01:41:22.560 --> 01:41:25.560
[Guest]: He's only 14.

01:41:25.560 --> 01:41:28.320
[Guest]: And the court tries to figure out why he's died.

01:41:28.320 --> 01:41:32.280
[Guest]: And the high priests say that it's because of an evil in the world.

01:41:32.280 --> 01:41:33.280
[Guest]: And what is this evil?

01:41:33.280 --> 01:41:40.400
[Guest]: It is that a Shudra is performing penance by trying to, can't be the word read because

01:41:40.400 --> 01:41:41.400
[Guest]: he can't read.

01:41:41.400 --> 01:41:45.120
[Guest]: But he's speaking out words from the Veda, which he's not supposed to.

01:41:45.120 --> 01:41:47.800
[Guest]: Ram goes and beheads him.

01:41:47.800 --> 01:41:50.440
[Guest]: This is the name of the Shudra is Shambhuka.

01:41:50.440 --> 01:41:52.360
[Guest]: This is in the Valmikannamayana.

01:41:52.360 --> 01:41:57.880
[Guest]: That's what the faith, the basis of the faith is cast.

01:41:57.880 --> 01:42:02.560
[Guest]: You might say, no, it is an innovation.

01:42:02.560 --> 01:42:03.960
[Guest]: It's not the case.

01:42:03.960 --> 01:42:10.440
[Guest]: But if you open your eyes and look at the society, the distinction between Dalit and

01:42:10.440 --> 01:42:12.800
[Guest]: Brahmin is quite clear.

01:42:12.800 --> 01:42:14.160
[Guest]: The access is quite clear.

01:42:14.160 --> 01:42:18.400
[Guest]: The history of India, the modern history of India in terms of access to temples is not

01:42:18.400 --> 01:42:21.600
[Guest]: that old.

01:42:21.600 --> 01:42:26.880
[Guest]: What is it that we use from that faith to be able to make India a proper Hindu Rashtra?

01:42:26.880 --> 01:42:28.880
[Guest]: We can discriminate against minorities.

01:42:28.880 --> 01:42:32.880
[Guest]: That's what most of these states in South Asia have sort of ended up doing.

01:42:32.880 --> 01:42:38.200
[Guest]: But what part of the faith can we actually implement to make it a Hindu Rashtra for Hindus?

01:42:38.200 --> 01:42:43.760
[Guest]: You can have a Hindu Rashtra for Muslims, you know, you can't, you can't stand for PM.

01:42:43.760 --> 01:42:45.440
[Guest]: Pakistan discriminated through law.

01:42:45.440 --> 01:42:47.120
[Guest]: We've done it through a practice.

01:42:47.120 --> 01:42:51.400
[Guest]: It's impossible to conceive of a Muslim becoming the PM of this country.

01:42:51.400 --> 01:42:55.880
[Guest]: Maybe in a coalition, but even that would be difficult.

01:42:55.880 --> 01:43:02.040
[Guest]: What part of the Hindu faith can we reduce and say that this is something that is applicable

01:43:02.040 --> 01:43:05.400
[Guest]: to modernity that's missing right now that will make us more pious?

01:43:05.400 --> 01:43:09.280
[Guest]: I think that fundamentally that is the question.

01:43:09.280 --> 01:43:12.440
[Guest]: For the Pakistanis, it became things like Riba.

01:43:12.440 --> 01:43:20.240
[Guest]: So Jesus says that he chucks the money changers, they're called out of the temple and usury

01:43:20.240 --> 01:43:25.120
[Guest]: becomes a bad word in the Semitic faiths.

01:43:25.120 --> 01:43:32.160
[Guest]: So for centuries, the Jews have a monopoly in Europe on access to capital, they are the

01:43:32.160 --> 01:43:35.760
[Guest]: only ones who can charge you no interest.

01:43:35.760 --> 01:43:42.000
[Guest]: Though Islam is much closer to Judaism than it is to Christianity, and it brings back

01:43:42.000 --> 01:43:47.960
[Guest]: indeed into the Semitic faiths, the ideas of circumcision and you know, pork and things

01:43:47.960 --> 01:43:50.200
[Guest]: like that.

01:43:50.200 --> 01:43:55.800
[Guest]: From Christianity, they take the idea that usury is a sin.

01:43:55.800 --> 01:44:01.220
[Guest]: The problem is that there's no modern banking system in the seventh century.

01:44:01.220 --> 01:44:06.320
[Guest]: But all three of Pakistan's constitutions have has the same writing that the state shall

01:44:06.320 --> 01:44:09.240
[Guest]: try to eliminate Riba.

01:44:09.240 --> 01:44:17.120
[Guest]: What happens is that the Supreme Court in 1999 and in 2000 abolished interest.

01:44:17.120 --> 01:44:20.080
[Guest]: You pass an order saying interest henceforth is abolished.

01:44:20.080 --> 01:44:23.880
[Guest]: But the modern economy will collapse, there is no replacement.

01:44:23.880 --> 01:44:29.360
[Guest]: What is the justification that if we do this, we'll get the blessings from God because we're

01:44:29.360 --> 01:44:30.920
[Guest]: doing this pious thing.

01:44:30.920 --> 01:44:33.160
[Guest]: That's not how modern states work.

01:44:33.160 --> 01:44:40.880
[Guest]: Pakistan, there are five pillars of Islam, Shahada, Som, Salah, Zakat, Hajj.

01:44:40.880 --> 01:44:44.160
[Guest]: So let's take fasting.

01:44:44.160 --> 01:44:49.840
[Guest]: In Dubai, like in many of the Gulf states in Ramzan, they shut, you know, restaurants

01:44:49.840 --> 01:44:55.600
[Guest]: have to be shut in the period of Ramzan, you know, till dusk, and that maybe makes the

01:44:55.600 --> 01:44:56.600
[Guest]: state a little more pious.

01:44:56.600 --> 01:44:58.120
[Guest]: You can actually implement that.

01:44:58.120 --> 01:45:00.600
[Guest]: You're trying to enforce your faith onto law.

01:45:00.600 --> 01:45:04.180
[Guest]: That's one way of doing it.

01:45:04.180 --> 01:45:06.920
[Guest]: You can do that with, Pakistan tried to do that with Zakat.

01:45:06.920 --> 01:45:11.120
[Guest]: So that is alms or a tax.

01:45:11.120 --> 01:45:16.320
[Guest]: So under Zia, what they say is, okay, on the first of Ramzan, we will deduct two and a

01:45:16.320 --> 01:45:23.960
[Guest]: half percent from all the bank deposits that are there, except for non-Sunnis.

01:45:23.960 --> 01:45:27.000
[Guest]: So because the Shia have their own clergy and they give their own money to them and

01:45:27.000 --> 01:45:28.040
[Guest]: so on.

01:45:28.040 --> 01:45:31.120
[Guest]: What started happening was Sunnis started declaring themselves Shia, not have the money

01:45:31.120 --> 01:45:35.080
[Guest]: deducted from their accounts, and then they had to water down that law.

01:45:35.080 --> 01:45:37.000
[Amit Varma]: Which shows humans will game anything, even religion.

01:45:37.000 --> 01:45:43.720
[Guest]: Indeed, I'm saying it's not possible to take a set of philosophical ideas, constructs,

01:45:43.720 --> 01:45:52.720
[Guest]: precepts, faith, belief type thing, and apply it to the modern world in the misplaced thinking

01:45:52.720 --> 01:45:57.000
[Guest]: that this will in some way improve your country and therefore Hindu Rashtra for it to become

01:45:57.000 --> 01:45:58.920
[Guest]: Hindu and non-discriminatory.

01:45:58.920 --> 01:46:01.840
[Guest]: I can completely understand the fact that when we say Hindu Rashtra, we'll say we'll

01:46:01.840 --> 01:46:02.840
[Guest]: kick the Muslims out.

01:46:02.840 --> 01:46:03.840
[Guest]: They can go to Pakistan.

01:46:03.840 --> 01:46:04.840
[Guest]: They can't eat beef.

01:46:04.840 --> 01:46:07.800
[Guest]: They have to give us their mosque.

01:46:07.800 --> 01:46:12.160
[Guest]: They have to give us their constitutional autonomy in Kashmir.

01:46:12.160 --> 01:46:14.640
[Guest]: They have to surrender their personal law.

01:46:14.640 --> 01:46:15.840
[Guest]: All that is fine.

01:46:15.840 --> 01:46:17.640
[Guest]: What does Hindu Rashtra offer Hindus?

01:46:17.640 --> 01:46:19.600
[Guest]: I think that is the problem.

01:46:19.600 --> 01:46:26.040
[Guest]: The question is that it doesn't have anything inside the faith that can be imposed.

01:46:26.040 --> 01:46:30.720
[Guest]: And that's a good thing in the way that Islam was able to impose, say, prayer or fasting

01:46:30.720 --> 01:46:35.040
[Guest]: or, you know, the abolition of interest.

01:46:35.040 --> 01:46:36.600
[Guest]: That's what makes it impossible.

01:46:36.600 --> 01:46:42.120
[Guest]: But that also brings the focus entirely onto minorities and discrimination.

01:46:42.120 --> 01:46:47.500
[Guest]: The only way that Hindutva can express itself is in negative terms.

01:46:47.500 --> 01:46:49.960
[Guest]: It cannot express itself in positive terms.

01:46:49.960 --> 01:46:57.080
[Guest]: The three primary demands of a political Hindutva is, you know, surrender your mosque, surrender

01:46:57.080 --> 01:47:03.040
[Guest]: your personal law, surrender your constitutional autonomy in Kashmir.

01:47:03.040 --> 01:47:09.240
[Guest]: There is there is nothing positive that it demands that will create a new or a vibrant

01:47:09.240 --> 01:47:10.240
[Amit Varma]: nation.

01:47:10.240 --> 01:47:14.040
[Amit Varma]: And yet it has such momentum in our electoral politics and in our culture.

01:47:14.040 --> 01:47:19.560
[Amit Varma]: So is it that people are then so full of hate and bigotry that this is so appealing to them?

01:47:19.560 --> 01:47:21.200
[Guest]: I think two things.

01:47:21.200 --> 01:47:25.820
[Guest]: I think that we should examine what you've just said.

01:47:25.820 --> 01:47:29.760
[Guest]: If you feel disturbed and I feel disturbed and many of us feel disturbed with the way

01:47:29.760 --> 01:47:33.160
[Guest]: that the beef lynching is a new phenomenon.

01:47:33.160 --> 01:47:35.160
[Guest]: We have introduced it to our to our country.

01:47:35.160 --> 01:47:41.360
[Guest]: It didn't exist just like the blasphemy lynchings did not exist in Pakistan till the law came

01:47:41.360 --> 01:47:51.200
[Guest]: to be till Maharashtra and Haryana did not act on the law in late 2014 in 2015.

01:47:51.200 --> 01:47:54.460
[Guest]: And the PM had not expressed himself strongly.

01:47:54.460 --> 01:48:00.420
[Guest]: We did not have the phenomenon of lynching on the issue of beef.

01:48:00.420 --> 01:48:03.160
[Guest]: This is new.

01:48:03.160 --> 01:48:04.960
[Guest]: We have gifted it to ourselves.

01:48:04.960 --> 01:48:10.440
[Guest]: And I think that we should ask ourselves, why don't more Indians recoil from this?

01:48:10.440 --> 01:48:12.740
[Guest]: I don't know the answer to it.

01:48:12.740 --> 01:48:18.040
[Guest]: But having said that, it is also the case that the BJP is a normal political party in

01:48:18.040 --> 01:48:26.220
[Guest]: India with a base that in large measure is based on caste and based on divisions at the

01:48:26.220 --> 01:48:29.600
[Guest]: local level and not particularly on any kind of ideology.

01:48:29.600 --> 01:48:34.040
[Amit Varma]: So I'm again thinking aloud here, trying to think about possibilities for why we don't

01:48:34.040 --> 01:48:35.440
[Amit Varma]: recoil from this.

01:48:35.440 --> 01:48:40.300
[Amit Varma]: And one thing that I've kind of believed is that look, all of us contain multitudes.

01:48:40.300 --> 01:48:44.800
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, just as the Hindu guy who's a bigot and who supports this narrative and

01:48:44.800 --> 01:48:51.420
[Amit Varma]: who wants to see a Hindu Rashtra, but there are other facets of him beyond this bigotry.

01:48:51.420 --> 01:48:57.440
[Amit Varma]: He also wants to be prosperous, he also wants to go to a concert, he also wants to do whatever.

01:48:57.440 --> 01:49:03.640
[Amit Varma]: And there just aren't enough narratives appealing to the better angels of the nature, as you

01:49:03.640 --> 01:49:04.640
[Amit Varma]: might say.

01:49:04.640 --> 01:49:10.440
[Amit Varma]: So is it then the case that this is also a cultural failure on the part of others to

01:49:10.440 --> 01:49:15.600
[Amit Varma]: create those narratives and a political failure on the part of other political parties to

01:49:15.600 --> 01:49:19.080
[Amit Varma]: come up with appealing narratives that can counter the Hindutva narrative?

01:49:19.080 --> 01:49:20.440
[Guest]: I don't know.

01:49:20.440 --> 01:49:25.340
[Guest]: But I think that you are on to something when you say what you just did, that there is an

01:49:25.340 --> 01:49:35.660
[Guest]: absence of narrative to the side of the kind of faith based, hate based stuff that is appealing

01:49:35.660 --> 01:49:37.240
[Guest]: to large numbers of people.

01:49:37.240 --> 01:49:38.700
[Guest]: I certainly don't see it.

01:49:38.700 --> 01:49:40.120
[Guest]: Maybe it's there and I don't see it.

01:49:40.120 --> 01:49:44.520
[Guest]: You know, you could be you could be in India and be reading the newspaper and not seeing

01:49:44.520 --> 01:49:50.060
[Guest]: many things, you know, and that's normally it's a large, it's a very large place.

01:49:50.060 --> 01:49:54.800
[Guest]: But to the extent that there is a non hate based narrative, even that seems to me to

01:49:54.800 --> 01:50:01.520
[Guest]: be controlled by the BJP, the idea of modernity through nationalism, the idea of non dynastic

01:50:01.520 --> 01:50:07.560
[Guest]: politics, the idea of honesty in politics, you know, a lot of that seems to be owned

01:50:07.560 --> 01:50:17.760
[Guest]: by the BJP, especially since Modi and it might well be that it's a failure of the other side

01:50:17.760 --> 01:50:23.900
[Guest]: to put forward something that is appealing, but I find it disturbing that more people

01:50:23.900 --> 01:50:28.520
[Guest]: are not upset by the morning newspaper.

01:50:28.520 --> 01:50:30.700
[Amit Varma]: It seems to me to be strange.

01:50:30.700 --> 01:50:35.080
[Amit Varma]: On that note, I've taken enough of your time, I'll ask you one final question, which I usually

01:50:35.080 --> 01:50:40.240
[Amit Varma]: ask my guests on whatever the subject we're talking about is, which is I asked him what

01:50:40.240 --> 01:50:43.640
[Amit Varma]: makes him hope and what makes him despair, but I'll be a little more specific.

01:50:43.640 --> 01:50:44.760
[Amit Varma]: I'll say that.

01:50:44.760 --> 01:50:47.560
[Amit Varma]: Number one, what is at stake in these elections?

01:50:47.560 --> 01:50:52.600
[Amit Varma]: And number two, within a 10 year window of time, the next 10 years, what is your best

01:50:52.600 --> 01:50:53.960
[Amit Varma]: case scenario for India?

01:50:53.960 --> 01:50:55.520
[Amit Varma]: And what is your worst case scenario?

01:50:55.520 --> 01:51:05.240
[Guest]: There's this funny line, there's this old poet, who's, who's asked, you know, okay,

01:51:05.240 --> 01:51:17.120
[Guest]: he says, I think that our fear is not that we will deteriorate into something worse.

01:51:17.120 --> 01:51:21.800
[Guest]: But the fact that we are okay with how bad it is now.

01:51:21.800 --> 01:51:24.600
[Amit Varma]: That what has been normalized now would be the worst case scenario.

01:51:24.600 --> 01:51:29.800
[Guest]: Indeed, indeed, this is a weird country, you've got violence in Kashmir, including the deaths

01:51:29.800 --> 01:51:38.760
[Guest]: of the armed forces higher in 2018, than in 2014, and higher, progressively so.

01:51:38.760 --> 01:51:48.160
[Guest]: To claim deterrence or to claim a hard military posture in the face of data, to me is astonishing.

01:51:48.160 --> 01:51:56.600
[Guest]: I mean, you slap me and I kicked you to whatever end, but the damage here done to me and my

01:51:56.600 --> 01:51:58.880
[Guest]: own is real.

01:51:58.880 --> 01:52:02.720
[Guest]: But it doesn't seem to really affect the narrative.

01:52:02.720 --> 01:52:07.360
[Guest]: In the larger media space, we are seen as being doing some some great things, you know,

01:52:07.360 --> 01:52:11.920
[Guest]: so it's bad enough as it is, I hope it doesn't get worse.

01:52:11.920 --> 01:52:19.000
[Guest]: I think we have enough within the within our societies, and I think that we have more than

01:52:19.000 --> 01:52:21.640
[Guest]: one to offer resistance.

01:52:21.640 --> 01:52:29.760
[Guest]: I don't think that we are all the same as a Gujarat, I think Gujarat is special, in

01:52:29.760 --> 01:52:36.140
[Guest]: many ways, in good ways, in many ways in really bad ones.

01:52:36.140 --> 01:52:40.000
[Guest]: But I don't think that the rest of the country is like that at all.

01:52:40.000 --> 01:52:43.040
[Amit Varma]: So what makes you despair is that it's more of the same?

01:52:43.040 --> 01:52:45.000
[Guest]: Yeah, I think it's not going away.

01:52:45.000 --> 01:52:47.800
[Guest]: I think that we have to live with this for a very long time.

01:52:47.800 --> 01:52:49.760
[Guest]: It doesn't matter who wins.

01:52:49.760 --> 01:52:50.760
[Guest]: In 2019.

01:52:50.760 --> 01:52:58.880
[Guest]: I think the idea that we have normalized violence against individuals who are vulnerable, the

01:52:58.880 --> 01:53:05.720
[Guest]: idea that we can marginalize people entirely, a community which has what 160 70 million

01:53:05.720 --> 01:53:10.960
[Guest]: people out of our legislatures, and it's okay.

01:53:10.960 --> 01:53:12.560
[Guest]: To me, that is unacceptable.

01:53:12.560 --> 01:53:16.840
[Guest]: But it seems to be fine for for most of us.

01:53:16.840 --> 01:53:19.280
[Guest]: And I don't think that's going to change anytime soon.

01:53:19.280 --> 01:53:26.480
[Amit Varma]: On that hopeful note, Aakar, thanks so much for coming on the scene, it was really insightful.

01:53:26.480 --> 01:53:30.760
[Amit Varma]: If you enjoyed listening to the show, do go directly to the source and read the books

01:53:30.760 --> 01:53:35.720
[Amit Varma]: Aakar and I spoke about by Savarkar, Golwalkar and Dindyal Upadhyay, which are linked from

01:53:35.720 --> 01:53:36.720
[Amit Varma]: the show notes.

01:53:36.720 --> 01:53:39.880
[Amit Varma]: Both Aakar and I could be biased against Hindutva.

01:53:39.880 --> 01:53:41.860
[Amit Varma]: So please do make up your own mind.

01:53:41.860 --> 01:53:45.880
[Amit Varma]: You can follow Aakar's columns online by putting a Google alert for him or just searching for

01:53:45.880 --> 01:53:47.280
[Amit Varma]: his name on Google News.

01:53:47.280 --> 01:53:50.760
